{"title_page": "Gargoyle Magazine", "text_new": "{{see also| Gargoyle Humor Magazine }}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title         = Gargoyle Magazine| editor = [[Richard Peabody]], [[Lucinda Ebersole]]\n| category = [[Literary magazine]]\n| publisher = Paycock Press \n| country = [[United States]]\n| frequency = \n| firstdate = 1976\n| website= {{URL|http://www.gargoylemagazine.com}}\n| oclc = \n| issn= 0162-1149\n}}\n'''''Gargoyle Magazine''''' is a [[literary magazine]] based in [[Washington, D.C.]]. It was established in 1976 by Russell Cox, [[Richard Peabody]], and Paul Pasquarella. By 1977, Peabody was the only remaining original editor. He continued running the magazine until 1990 with several different co-editors.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/73823585.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=May+26,+1987&author=Mary+Battiata&pub=The+Washington+Post+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&edition=&startpage=e.01&desc=The+Gargoyle+Chronicles;+The+End+of+a+Love+Affair+Could+Extinguish+a+Local+Literary+Light| title=The Gargoyle Chronicles; The End of a Love Affair Could Extinguish a Local Literary Light|work=The Washington Post|author=Mary Battiata|date= May 26, 1987}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72577779.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Mar+26,+1990&author=Todd+Allan+Yasui&pub=The+Washington+Post+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&edition=&startpage=b.07&desc=Gargoyle,+Quitting+the+Quest|title=Gargoyle, Quitting the Quest|work=The Washington Post|author=Todd Allan Yasui|date=March 26, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edrants.com/richard-peabody-mondo-literature/|title=Reluctant Habits|publisher=Edrants|date=May 19, 2007|accessdate=October 3, 2015}}</ref>  Before the magazine ceased publication in 1990, thirty-six issues had been released.It resurfaced in 1997 with Peabody and [[Lucinda Ebersole]] as editors and continues to this day. ''Gargoyle Magazine'' released its 71st issue in 2020. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pw.org/content/gargoyle_magazine|title=Poets & Writers |publisher=PW|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nGargoyle is dedicated to printing works by unknown poets and fiction writers, as well as seeking out the overlooked or neglected writers. Considered an anthology that publishes both local and international authors, the magazine featured poetry, fiction, articles, art, photos, interviews, satire, reviews, long poems, and novel excerpts.<ref name=GWU>[https://library.gwu.edu/ead/ms2040.xml Guide to the Richard M. Peabody Gargoyle Magazine Collection, circa 1976-2009], Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University</ref>  the magazine has published work by authors as diverse as Angela Threatt,<ref>{{cite web|last=Athitakis|first=Mark|url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/citydesk/2007/05/29/from-the-southern-city-of-washington-dc/ |title=From the Southern City of Washington D.C.|work=Washington city paper|date=May 29, 2007|accessdate=2015-10-03}}</ref> Joyce Renwick,<ref>{{cite web|last=Jamieson |first=Dave |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/28326/dear-reader |title=Dear Reader: Richard Peabody has lost thousands publishing Washington's foremost literary magazine. If only he actually liked it here. |publisher=Washington City Paper |date=2004-04-02 |accessdate=October 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Julia Slavin]], [[Mary Kay Zuravleff]], [[Ray Bradbury]], [[Kathy Acker]], [[Robert Peters (playwright)|Robert Peters]] and [[Nick Cave]]. ''Gargoyle'' has also published authors who have won the Pulitzer Prize, the MacArthur Fellowship, and the National Book Award among other honors.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/04/AR2011020405355.html| work=The Washington Post|title=Main Character: Richard Peabody has devoted his life to Washington's writers. At what cost?| author=Lora Engdahl|date=February 13, 2011}}</ref>  Each contributor receives one issue as compensation for their literary piece.<ref>[http://www.gwu.edu/gelman/spec/ead/ms2040.html Richard M. Peabody Gargoyle Magazine Collection] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629001919/http://www.gwu.edu/gelman/spec/ead/ms2040.html |date=2011-06-29 }}, Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University</ref> Work from the magazine has been included in The Best American Fantasy, The Best American Non-Required Reading, New Stories from the South, and The Year's Best Fantasy and Horror.\n\nIn 1999, the Magazine won a $7,500 grant from the [[London Arts Board]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bane |first=Colin |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/17528/you-can-lead-a-horse-to-books |title=You Can Lead a Horse to Books...: Richard Peabody and Lucinda Ebersole made Atticus Used Books a thriving nursery for the small press. So why does he want out? |work=Washington City Paper|date=July 12, 2013|accessdate=October 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe magazine's archive is housed in the Special Collections Research Center of the Estelle and Melvin [[Gelman Library]] at [[George Washington University]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://www.gargoylemagazine.com/}}\n*[https://library.gwu.edu/ead/ms2040.xml Guide to the Richard M. Peabody Gargoyle Magazine Collection, circa 1976-2009, Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gargoyle Magazine}}\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also| Gargoyle Humor Magazine }}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title         = Gargoyle Magazine| editor = [[Richard Peabody]], [[Lucinda Ebersole]]\n| category = [[Literary magazine]]\n| publisher = Paycock Press \n| country = [[United States]]\n| frequency = \n| firstdate = 1976\n| website= {{URL|http://www.gargoylemagazine.com}}\n| oclc = \n| issn= 0162-1149\n}}\n'''''Gargoyle Magazine''''' is a [[literary magazine]] based in [[Washington, D.C.]]. It was established in 1976 by Russell Cox, [[Richard Peabody]], and Paul Pasquarella. By 1977, Peabody was the only remaining original editor. He continued running the magazine until 1990 with several different co-editors.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/73823585.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=May+26,+1987&author=Mary+Battiata&pub=The+Washington+Post+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&edition=&startpage=e.01&desc=The+Gargoyle+Chronicles;+The+End+of+a+Love+Affair+Could+Extinguish+a+Local+Literary+Light| title=The Gargoyle Chronicles; The End of a Love Affair Could Extinguish a Local Literary Light|work=The Washington Post|author=Mary Battiata|date= May 26, 1987}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72577779.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Mar+26,+1990&author=Todd+Allan+Yasui&pub=The+Washington+Post+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&edition=&startpage=b.07&desc=Gargoyle,+Quitting+the+Quest|title=Gargoyle, Quitting the Quest|work=The Washington Post|author=Todd Allan Yasui|date=March 26, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edrants.com/richard-peabody-mondo-literature/|title=Reluctant Habits|publisher=Edrants|date=May 19, 2007|accessdate=October 3, 2015}}</ref>  Before the magazine ceased publication in 1990, thirty-six issues had been released.It resurfaced in 1997 with Peabody and [[Lucinda Ebersole]] as editors and continues to this day. ''Gargoyle Magazine'' released its 71st issue in 2020. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pw.org/content/gargoyle_magazine|title=Poets & Writers |publisher=PW|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nGargoyle is dedicated to printing works by unknown poets and fiction writers, as well as seeking out the overlooked or neglected writers. Considered an anthology that publishes both local and international authors, the magazine featured poetry, fiction, articles, art, photos, interviews, satire, reviews, long poems, and novel excerpts.<ref name=GWU>[https://library.gwu.edu/ead/ms2040.xml Guide to the Richard M. Peabody Gargoyle Magazine Collection, circa 1976-2009], Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University</ref>  the magazine has published work by authors as diverse as Angela Threatt,<ref>{{cite web|last=Athitakis|first=Mark|url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/citydesk/2007/05/29/from-the-southern-city-of-washington-dc/ |title=From the Southern City of Washington D.C.|work=Washington city paper|date=May 29, 2007|accessdate=2015-10-03}}</ref> Joyce Renwick,<ref>{{cite web|last=Jamieson |first=Dave |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/28326/dear-reader |title=Dear Reader: Richard Peabody has lost thousands publishing Washington's foremost literary magazine. If only he actually liked it here. |publisher=Washington City Paper |date=2004-04-02 |accessdate=October 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Julia Slavin]], [[Mary Kay Zuravleff]], [[Ray Bradbury]], [[Kathy Acker]], [[Robert Peters]] and [[Nick Cave]]. ''Gargoyle'' has also published authors who have won the Pulitzer Prize, the MacArthur Fellowship, and the National Book Award among other honors.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/04/AR2011020405355.html| work=The Washington Post|title=Main Character: Richard Peabody has devoted his life to Washington's writers. At what cost?| author=Lora Engdahl|date=February 13, 2011}}</ref>  Each contributor receives one issue as compensation for their literary piece.<ref>[http://www.gwu.edu/gelman/spec/ead/ms2040.html Richard M. Peabody Gargoyle Magazine Collection] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629001919/http://www.gwu.edu/gelman/spec/ead/ms2040.html |date=2011-06-29 }}, Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University</ref> Work from the magazine has been included in The Best American Fantasy, The Best American Non-Required Reading, New Stories from the South, and The Year's Best Fantasy and Horror.\n\nIn 1999, the Magazine won a $7,500 grant from the [[London Arts Board]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bane |first=Colin |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/17528/you-can-lead-a-horse-to-books |title=You Can Lead a Horse to Books...: Richard Peabody and Lucinda Ebersole made Atticus Used Books a thriving nursery for the small press. So why does he want out? |work=Washington City Paper|date=July 12, 2013|accessdate=October 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe magazine's archive is housed in the Special Collections Research Center of the Estelle and Melvin [[Gelman Library]] at [[George Washington University]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://www.gargoylemagazine.com/}}\n*[https://library.gwu.edu/ead/ms2040.xml Guide to the Richard M. Peabody Gargoyle Magazine Collection, circa 1976-2009, Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gargoyle Magazine}}\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRobert Peters(link changed toRobert Peters (playwright)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gargoyle_Magazine"}
{"title_page": "George Hitchcock (poet)", "text_new": "'''George Parks Hitchcock''' (June 2, 1914 \u2013 August 27, 2010) was an [[United States|American]] [[actor]], [[poet]], [[playwright]], [[teacher]], [[Union organizer|labor activist]], [[Publishing|publisher]], and [[Painting|painter]]. He is best known for creating ''[[Kayak (magazine)|Kayak]]'', a poetry magazine that he published as a one-man operation from 1964 to 1984.<ref name=NYTObit>{{cite news|title=George Hitchcock, Kayak Magazine Founder, Dies at 96|first=William|last=Grimes|date=September 4, 2010|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 4, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/04/arts/04hitchcock.html}}</ref> Equally important, Hitchcock published writers under the \"Kayak\" imprint including the first two books by [[Charles Simic]], second books by [[Philip Levine (poet)|Philip Levine]] and [[Raymond Carver]], translations by [[W.S. Merwin]], and early books by [[Robert Bly]] and [[James Tate (writer)|James Tate]].<ref name=AAPtribute>{{cite news|title=In Memoriam: George Hitchcock|first=Robert|last=McDowell|date=|accessdate=September 10, 2010|url=http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/21840}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHitchcock was born in [[Hood River, Oregon|Hood River]], [[Oregon]], graduating in 1935 from the [[University of Oregon]], where he was a reporter on the school newspaper. After college, he worked as a journalist for several labor movement periodicals, including ''[https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/westernworker/1933/index.htm The Western Worker]'' and ''The People\u2019s Daily World'', simultaneously developing an interest in poetry which was fostered by [[Kenneth Rexroth]]. He joined the [[United States Merchant Marine]] during [[World War II]], and worked as a cook and a waiter in the South Pacific.<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\nAfter the war, he became more active in the labor movement, working to organize dairy workers in California and teaching at the [[California Labor School]]. Later, he became active in the [[San Francisco]] theater scene, writing plays and acting with the [[Actor's Workshop]] and the [[Interplayers Theater|Interplayers]] while working as a landscape gardener.<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\nWhile performing at the [[Oregon Shakespeare Festival]] in 1957, Hitchcock was called to testify before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]], where in response to a question asking him his profession, he responded, \"I am a gardener. I do underground work on plants\". He refused to answer any further questions \"on the grounds that this hearing is a big bore and waste of the public's money\".<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\n==Magazine publisher==\nIn 1958, after the ''[[San Francisco Review]]'' published one of Hitchcock's plays, he joined it as an editor. When the organization folded, he founded ''Kayak'' as a response to what he saw as the \"tepid eclecticism\" of the other literary journals of the day, with the journal's title representing the \"small watertight vessel operated by a single oarsman\" that was a metaphor for the way he personally ran the publication as a self-titled \"dictator\".<ref name=LATObit>Woo, Elaine. [http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-george-hitchcock-20100902,0,3051524.story \"George Hitchcock dies at 96; poet and publisher of the literary magazine 'kayak': Hitchcock created kayak in 1964, and it quickly gained notice as a bulwark on the literary vanguard. It provided a forum for such writers as Robert Bly, Raymond Carver, W.S. Merwin and Anne Sexton.\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', September 2, 2010. Accessed September 5, 2010.</ref> Hitchcock ran ''Kayak'' frugally as a one-man show from its creation in 1964, using an [[offset printing]] press he had purchased and having personally \"designed the magazine, edited it, printed it, illustrated it\" and ran parties where the printed sheets would be assembled for mailing.<ref name=NYTObit/> \n\nDuring his Kayak period in San Francisco, ca. 1967, he was on the adjunct faculty of [[San Francisco State University|San Francisco State]] and taught a lively graduate level playwriting course out of his home on Webster Street\u2014three hours in the evening once a week\u2014where students effectively performed scenes they had written for assignments; often visiting poets like Robert Bly and other Kayak writers dropped in for a cup of coffee and observed quietly from the kitchen. \n\nHitchcock moved to [[Santa Cruz, California]] in 1970 and joined the faculty of the [[University of California, Santa Cruz]], where he taught poetry and playwriting until 1989. In the magazine's 64 issues published before he shut the publication in 1984, ''Kayak'' included many significant poets and writers of prose, such as [[Raymond Carver]], [[Anne Sexton]], [[Robert Bly]], and [[Margaret Atwood]].<ref name=\"NYTObit\" /> [[Howard Junker]], founder and editor of ''[[Zyzzyva (magazine)|Zyzzyva: The Journal of West Coast Writers and Artists]]'', called Hitchcock \"the pre-eminent maverick independent magazine publisher\".<ref name=\"NYTObit\" />\n\nHitchcock had co-written a critical satire Pioneers of Modern Poetry with poet [[Robert Peters (playwright)|Robert Peters]] in 1966. It was led to be an experiment in criticism. In these pieces where Hitchcock arranged most of the \"poems\" from various prose texts, and Peters wrote most of the \"interpretations.\" These ripostes between Hitchcock & Peters were thrust against some of the excesses of Projective Verse poets, their adulators, and academic readings of poems.<ref>https://openlibrary.org/works/OL2907307W/Pioneers_of_modern_poetry</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nHitchcock died at age 96 on August 27, 2010, at his home in [[Eugene, Oregon]]. He was survived by his companion, Marjorie Simon, as well as by a son, two grandchildren and a great-grandchild.<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\nA Tribute to George Hitchcock was published in [http://caneilson.blogspot.com/ ViVACE 2 Literary Magazine] in 2010. Included in the tribute were quirky vignettes by Hitchcock's fellow poets, colleagues, friends and former students. ViVACE was founded by one of Hitchcock's former UCSC students Christine Neilson in 2009.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/21840 In Memoriam: George Hitchcock] by Robert McDowell, at the [[Academy of American Poets]] website \n*[http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/21842 \"Dawn\"] on-line poem by Hitchcock, first published in his volume ''A Ship of Bells''\n*[http://georgehitchcock.blogspot.com/ \"A Bit About My Father\"] Memorial Blog by his son Stephen.\n*[http://www.kayakattheconfluence.org Kayak at the Confluence: A Tribute to George Hitchcock] by Liz Wiley, poetry symposium held March 19, 2011 in St. Louis, Missouri.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hitchcock, George Parks}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:Poets from Oregon]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Eugene, Oregon]]\n[[Category:United States Merchant Mariners]]\n[[Category:United States Merchant Mariners of World War II]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Cruz faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Oregon alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n", "text_old": "'''George Parks Hitchcock''' (June 2, 1914 \u2013 August 27, 2010) was an [[United States|American]] [[actor]], [[poet]], [[playwright]], [[teacher]], [[Union organizer|labor activist]], [[Publishing|publisher]], and [[Painting|painter]]. He is best known for creating ''[[Kayak (magazine)|Kayak]]'', a poetry magazine that he published as a one-man operation from 1964 to 1984.<ref name=NYTObit>{{cite news|title=George Hitchcock, Kayak Magazine Founder, Dies at 96|first=William|last=Grimes|date=September 4, 2010|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 4, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/04/arts/04hitchcock.html}}</ref> Equally important, Hitchcock published writers under the \"Kayak\" imprint including the first two books by [[Charles Simic]], second books by [[Philip Levine (poet)|Philip Levine]] and [[Raymond Carver]], translations by [[W.S. Merwin]], and early books by [[Robert Bly]] and [[James Tate (writer)|James Tate]].<ref name=AAPtribute>{{cite news|title=In Memoriam: George Hitchcock|first=Robert|last=McDowell|date=|accessdate=September 10, 2010|url=http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/21840}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHitchcock was born in [[Hood River, Oregon|Hood River]], [[Oregon]], graduating in 1935 from the [[University of Oregon]], where he was a reporter on the school newspaper. After college, he worked as a journalist for several labor movement periodicals, including ''[https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/westernworker/1933/index.htm The Western Worker]'' and ''The People\u2019s Daily World'', simultaneously developing an interest in poetry which was fostered by [[Kenneth Rexroth]]. He joined the [[United States Merchant Marine]] during [[World War II]], and worked as a cook and a waiter in the South Pacific.<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\nAfter the war, he became more active in the labor movement, working to organize dairy workers in California and teaching at the [[California Labor School]]. Later, he became active in the [[San Francisco]] theater scene, writing plays and acting with the [[Actor's Workshop]] and the [[Interplayers Theater|Interplayers]] while working as a landscape gardener.<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\nWhile performing at the [[Oregon Shakespeare Festival]] in 1957, Hitchcock was called to testify before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]], where in response to a question asking him his profession, he responded, \"I am a gardener. I do underground work on plants\". He refused to answer any further questions \"on the grounds that this hearing is a big bore and waste of the public's money\".<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\n==Magazine publisher==\nIn 1958, after the ''[[San Francisco Review]]'' published one of Hitchcock's plays, he joined it as an editor. When the organization folded, he founded ''Kayak'' as a response to what he saw as the \"tepid eclecticism\" of the other literary journals of the day, with the journal's title representing the \"small watertight vessel operated by a single oarsman\" that was a metaphor for the way he personally ran the publication as a self-titled \"dictator\".<ref name=LATObit>Woo, Elaine. [http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-george-hitchcock-20100902,0,3051524.story \"George Hitchcock dies at 96; poet and publisher of the literary magazine 'kayak': Hitchcock created kayak in 1964, and it quickly gained notice as a bulwark on the literary vanguard. It provided a forum for such writers as Robert Bly, Raymond Carver, W.S. Merwin and Anne Sexton.\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', September 2, 2010. Accessed September 5, 2010.</ref> Hitchcock ran ''Kayak'' frugally as a one-man show from its creation in 1964, using an [[offset printing]] press he had purchased and having personally \"designed the magazine, edited it, printed it, illustrated it\" and ran parties where the printed sheets would be assembled for mailing.<ref name=NYTObit/> \n\nDuring his Kayak period in San Francisco, ca. 1967, he was on the adjunct faculty of [[San Francisco State University|San Francisco State]] and taught a lively graduate level playwriting course out of his home on Webster Street\u2014three hours in the evening once a week\u2014where students effectively performed scenes they had written for assignments; often visiting poets like Robert Bly and other Kayak writers dropped in for a cup of coffee and observed quietly from the kitchen. \n\nHitchcock moved to [[Santa Cruz, California]] in 1970 and joined the faculty of the [[University of California, Santa Cruz]], where he taught poetry and playwriting until 1989. In the magazine's 64 issues published before he shut the publication in 1984, ''Kayak'' included many significant poets and writers of prose, such as [[Raymond Carver]], [[Anne Sexton]], [[Robert Bly]], and [[Margaret Atwood]].<ref name=\"NYTObit\" /> [[Howard Junker]], founder and editor of ''[[Zyzzyva (magazine)|Zyzzyva: The Journal of West Coast Writers and Artists]]'', called Hitchcock \"the pre-eminent maverick independent magazine publisher\".<ref name=\"NYTObit\" />\n\nHitchcock had co-written a critical satire Pioneers of Modern Poetry with poet [[Robert Peters]] in 1966. It was led to be an experiment in criticism. In these pieces where Hitchcock arranged most of the \"poems\" from various prose texts, and Peters wrote most of the \"interpretations.\" These ripostes between Hitchcock & Peters were thrust against some of the excesses of Projective Verse poets, their adulators, and academic readings of poems.<ref>https://openlibrary.org/works/OL2907307W/Pioneers_of_modern_poetry</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nHitchcock died at age 96 on August 27, 2010, at his home in [[Eugene, Oregon]]. He was survived by his companion, Marjorie Simon, as well as by a son, two grandchildren and a great-grandchild.<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\nA Tribute to George Hitchcock was published in [http://caneilson.blogspot.com/ ViVACE 2 Literary Magazine] in 2010. Included in the tribute were quirky vignettes by Hitchcock's fellow poets, colleagues, friends and former students. ViVACE was founded by one of Hitchcock's former UCSC students Christine Neilson in 2009.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/21840 In Memoriam: George Hitchcock] by Robert McDowell, at the [[Academy of American Poets]] website \n*[http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/21842 \"Dawn\"] on-line poem by Hitchcock, first published in his volume ''A Ship of Bells''\n*[http://georgehitchcock.blogspot.com/ \"A Bit About My Father\"] Memorial Blog by his son Stephen.\n*[http://www.kayakattheconfluence.org Kayak at the Confluence: A Tribute to George Hitchcock] by Liz Wiley, poetry symposium held March 19, 2011 in St. Louis, Missouri.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hitchcock, George Parks}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:Poets from Oregon]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Eugene, Oregon]]\n[[Category:United States Merchant Mariners]]\n[[Category:United States Merchant Mariners of World War II]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Cruz faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Oregon alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRobert Peters(link changed toRobert Peters (playwright)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Hitchcock_(poet)"}
{"title_page": "New Rivers Press", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=April 2010}}\n{{notability|Companies|date=April 2010}}\n{{COI|date=April 2010}}\n}}\n\n'''New Rivers Press''' is an American [[non-profit]] publishing press located in [[Moorhead, Minnesota]] and affiliated with [[Minnesota State University Moorhead]].\n\n==History and mission==\nNew Rivers Press was founded by C.W. \u201cBill\u201d Truesdale in 1968<ref>[http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/books/107764983.html ''Star Tribune.com''> November 13, 2010 > ''A Celebration of New Rivers Press'' > by Laurie Hertzel]</ref> out of an old barn in [[Massachusetts]]. The first title published by New Rivers Press was ''So Many Rooms Has a House But One Roof'', a poetry collection by [[Margaret Randall]]. The press moved to [[Minnesota]] in 1978, joining the thriving literary small press community in the Twin Cities of [[Minneapolis]] and [[Saint Paul]], that includes [[Coffee House Press]], [[Milkweed Editions]], and [[Graywolf Press]]. In 1982, the press became the first book publisher to obtain [[501(c)3]] [[Non-profit organization|nonprofit]] status.<ref>[newriverspress.com/ New Rivers Press]</ref> In 2001, when Truesdale died, the press went into suspension and later that year relocated to Minnesota State University Moorhead,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/904299055|title=Paper Camera : A Half Century with New Rivers Press|last=Suzzanne|first=Kelley|last2=Strnad Hoalcraft|first2=Alicia|publisher=New Rivers Press|year=2015|isbn=9780898233001|location=|pages=77\u201388|oclc=904299055|quote=|via=}}</ref> where it was revived under different management with a dual mission: to publish literature by new and emerging writers, honoring Truesdale's legacy, and to provide learning opportunities for students. Through collaborative efforts, New Rivers Press publishes enduring literary works and teaches the business of [[publishing]], offering the opportunity to earn a Certificate in Publishing while working as [[intern]]s to gain practical experience. The activities of the press and its related curriculum were integrated into the school\u2019s [[Master of Fine Arts]] in [[Creative Writing]] program until its termination in 2014, and also into [[accounting]], [[art]] and [[graphic design]], English, [[marketing]], [[mass communication]]s, promotions, and [[website]] development classes at MSUM. Cover [[design]]s for New Rivers Press by graphic design students were selected as winners in the 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, and 2013 American Inhouse Design Awards by Graphic Design USA.<ref>[http://www.newriverspress.com/ New Rivers Press > About Us]</ref>\n\n==Series, distribution and funding==\nNew Rivers Press book series include [[American Fiction]] Anthologies, American Fiction Series, [[American Poetry]] Series, Many Minnesotas Project, Many Voices Project, and the New Rivers Abroad Series. The press offers two national awards, The Many Voices Project Prose Prize, and the Many Voices Project Poetry Prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newriverspress.com/submissions/many-voices-project/|title=Many Voices Project \u2013 New Rivers Press|website=www.newriverspress.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-08}}</ref> New Rivers Press titles are distributed by Small Press Distribution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spdbooks.org/pages/publishers/Publisher-List-No-Description.aspx|title=Publisher List No Description : Small Press Distribution|website=www.spdbooks.org|access-date=2017-02-08}}</ref> New Rivers Press has received support from the [[McKnight Foundation]], the [[Jerome Foundation]], and individual donors.\n\n==Notable authors and honors==\nNotable authors include [[Diane Glancy]], Richard Hoffman, [[Charles Baxter (author)|Charles Baxter]], Kathryn Nocerino, James Bertolino, [[Robert Peters (playwright)|Robert Peters]], [[Warren Woessner]] and [[Albert Goldbarth]].  New Rivers Press titles have been reviewed in ''Publishers Weekly, Library Journal,''<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0898232287 Amazon.com > ''Half the House'' by Richard Hoffman > Editorial Reviews]</ref>  ''Booklist,''<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0898232333 Amazon.com > ''Not a Matter of Love'' by Beth Alvarado > Editorial Reviews]</ref> and ''Kirkus Reviews.''<ref>[http://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/fiction/ron-block/the-dirty-shame-hotel/ Kirkus Reviews > May 1, 1998 > ''The Dirty Shame Hotel and Other Stores'' by Ron Block]</ref>\n\n==Staff==\n* Senior Editor: Kevin Carollo\n* Director: Travis Dolence\n* Managing Editor: Nathan \"Nayt\" Rundquist\n* Former Poetry Editor: Thom Tammaro\n* New Rivers Abroad Editor and Many Voices Project Coordinator for Poetry: Kevin Carollo\n* Many Voices Project Coordinator for Prose: Vincent Reusch\n* New Rivers Press Electronic Book Series Associate Editor: Daniel Shudlick\n<ref>newriverspress.com</ref>\n<ref>http://us8.campaign-archive2.com/?u=2b32b15b3d31404daa1edf733&id=5ac5d9ab03&e=db2aeeeb46</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cbsd.com/pubdetail.aspx?id=258 Consortium Book Sales & Distribution > New Rivers Press Publisher Information]\n* [http://www.clmp.org/directory/index.php Council of Literary Magazines and Small Presses > Directory of Member Publishers]\n* [http://www.pw.org/content/new_rivers_press ''Poets & Writers'' Directory Listing: New Rivers Press]\n\n[[Category:Book publishing companies based in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Poetry publishers]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1968]]\n[[Category:Minnesota culture]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:University presses of the United States]]\n[[Category:Minnesota State University Moorhead]]\n[[Category:Non-profit publishers]]\n[[Category:1968 establishments in Minnesota]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=April 2010}}\n{{notability|Companies|date=April 2010}}\n{{COI|date=April 2010}}\n}}\n\n'''New Rivers Press''' is an American [[non-profit]] publishing press located in [[Moorhead, Minnesota]] and affiliated with [[Minnesota State University Moorhead]].\n\n==History and mission==\nNew Rivers Press was founded by C.W. \u201cBill\u201d Truesdale in 1968<ref>[http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/books/107764983.html ''Star Tribune.com''> November 13, 2010 > ''A Celebration of New Rivers Press'' > by Laurie Hertzel]</ref> out of an old barn in [[Massachusetts]]. The first title published by New Rivers Press was ''So Many Rooms Has a House But One Roof'', a poetry collection by [[Margaret Randall]]. The press moved to [[Minnesota]] in 1978, joining the thriving literary small press community in the Twin Cities of [[Minneapolis]] and [[Saint Paul]], that includes [[Coffee House Press]], [[Milkweed Editions]], and [[Graywolf Press]]. In 1982, the press became the first book publisher to obtain [[501(c)3]] [[Non-profit organization|nonprofit]] status.<ref>[newriverspress.com/ New Rivers Press]</ref> In 2001, when Truesdale died, the press went into suspension and later that year relocated to Minnesota State University Moorhead,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/904299055|title=Paper Camera : A Half Century with New Rivers Press|last=Suzzanne|first=Kelley|last2=Strnad Hoalcraft|first2=Alicia|publisher=New Rivers Press|year=2015|isbn=9780898233001|location=|pages=77\u201388|oclc=904299055|quote=|via=}}</ref> where it was revived under different management with a dual mission: to publish literature by new and emerging writers, honoring Truesdale's legacy, and to provide learning opportunities for students. Through collaborative efforts, New Rivers Press publishes enduring literary works and teaches the business of [[publishing]], offering the opportunity to earn a Certificate in Publishing while working as [[intern]]s to gain practical experience. The activities of the press and its related curriculum were integrated into the school\u2019s [[Master of Fine Arts]] in [[Creative Writing]] program until its termination in 2014, and also into [[accounting]], [[art]] and [[graphic design]], English, [[marketing]], [[mass communication]]s, promotions, and [[website]] development classes at MSUM. Cover [[design]]s for New Rivers Press by graphic design students were selected as winners in the 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, and 2013 American Inhouse Design Awards by Graphic Design USA.<ref>[http://www.newriverspress.com/ New Rivers Press > About Us]</ref>\n\n==Series, distribution and funding==\nNew Rivers Press book series include [[American Fiction]] Anthologies, American Fiction Series, [[American Poetry]] Series, Many Minnesotas Project, Many Voices Project, and the New Rivers Abroad Series. The press offers two national awards, The Many Voices Project Prose Prize, and the Many Voices Project Poetry Prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newriverspress.com/submissions/many-voices-project/|title=Many Voices Project \u2013 New Rivers Press|website=www.newriverspress.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-08}}</ref> New Rivers Press titles are distributed by Small Press Distribution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spdbooks.org/pages/publishers/Publisher-List-No-Description.aspx|title=Publisher List No Description : Small Press Distribution|website=www.spdbooks.org|access-date=2017-02-08}}</ref> New Rivers Press has received support from the [[McKnight Foundation]], the [[Jerome Foundation]], and individual donors.\n\n==Notable authors and honors==\nNotable authors include [[Diane Glancy]], Richard Hoffman, [[Charles Baxter (author)|Charles Baxter]], Kathryn Nocerino, James Bertolino, [[Robert Peters]], [[Warren Woessner]] and [[Albert Goldbarth]].  New Rivers Press titles have been reviewed in ''Publishers Weekly, Library Journal,''<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0898232287 Amazon.com > ''Half the House'' by Richard Hoffman > Editorial Reviews]</ref>  ''Booklist,''<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0898232333 Amazon.com > ''Not a Matter of Love'' by Beth Alvarado > Editorial Reviews]</ref> and ''Kirkus Reviews.''<ref>[http://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/fiction/ron-block/the-dirty-shame-hotel/ Kirkus Reviews > May 1, 1998 > ''The Dirty Shame Hotel and Other Stores'' by Ron Block]</ref>\n\n==Staff==\n* Senior Editor: Kevin Carollo\n* Director: Travis Dolence\n* Managing Editor: Nathan \"Nayt\" Rundquist\n* Former Poetry Editor: Thom Tammaro\n* New Rivers Abroad Editor and Many Voices Project Coordinator for Poetry: Kevin Carollo\n* Many Voices Project Coordinator for Prose: Vincent Reusch\n* New Rivers Press Electronic Book Series Associate Editor: Daniel Shudlick\n<ref>newriverspress.com</ref>\n<ref>http://us8.campaign-archive2.com/?u=2b32b15b3d31404daa1edf733&id=5ac5d9ab03&e=db2aeeeb46</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cbsd.com/pubdetail.aspx?id=258 Consortium Book Sales & Distribution > New Rivers Press Publisher Information]\n* [http://www.clmp.org/directory/index.php Council of Literary Magazines and Small Presses > Directory of Member Publishers]\n* [http://www.pw.org/content/new_rivers_press ''Poets & Writers'' Directory Listing: New Rivers Press]\n\n[[Category:Book publishing companies based in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Poetry publishers]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1968]]\n[[Category:Minnesota culture]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:University presses of the United States]]\n[[Category:Minnesota State University Moorhead]]\n[[Category:Non-profit publishers]]\n[[Category:1968 establishments in Minnesota]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRobert Peters(link changed toRobert Peters (playwright)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Rivers_Press"}
{"title_page": "Mahindra Group", "text_new": "{{otheruses|Mahindra (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2016}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Mahindra Group\n| logo = [[File:Mahindra Rise New Logo.svg|200px]]\n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|df=yes|1945}}\n| founder = [[Jagdish Chandra Mahindra]]<br />[[Kailash Chandra Mahindra]]<br /> [[Malik Ghulam Muhammad]]\n| location = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = [[Anand Mahindra]] (Chairman & MD)<br />[[Keshub Mahindra]] (Chairman emeritus)\n| industry = [[Conglomerate (company)|Conglomerate]]\n| products = {{hlist | [[Automotive]]  | [[IT Services]] | [[Finance]]| [[Hospitality industry|Hospitality]] |[[Agribusiness]] | [[Defense (military)|Defense]] }}\n| revenue = {{profit}} [[United States dollar|US$]]20.7 billion (2018)<ref>{{cite web|title=Corporate overview|url=http://www.mahindra.com/about-us|date= | accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>\n| num_employees = 240,000 (2018)<ref name=Annual>[http://www.mahindra.com/Who-We-Are/Overview/ Employee strength]</ref>\n| subsid = [[Mahindra & Mahindra]],<br> [[SsangYong Motor Company|SsangYong Motors]],<br> [[Mahindra Aerospace]],<br>[[Mahindra & Mahindra Financial Services Limited]],<br> Mahindra Systech,<br> [[Tech Mahindra]],<br> [[Mahindra Lifespace Developers]],<br> Mahindra Ugine Steel Company <br>[[BSA Company]]\n[[Automobili Pininfarina]],<br>\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.mahindra.com/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Mahindra Group''' is an Indian multinational [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] [[holding company]] headquartered in [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]. It has operations in over 100 countries around the globe. The group has a presence in aerospace, agribusiness, aftermarket, automotive, components, construction equipment, defence, energy, farm equipment, finance and insurance, industrial equipment, information technology, leisure and hospitality, logistics, real estate, retail, and two wheelers.  It is considered to be one of the most reputable Indian industrial houses<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2006/11/20/leadership-companies-reputation-lead-managing-cx_hc_1120indarep_slide_9.html?thisSpeed=15000 |title=India's Most Reputable Companies |publisher=Forbes.com |date=2006-11-20 |accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref> with market leadership in utility vehicles<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/businessNews/idINIndia-41345620090727 |title=BSE Sensex little changed; Reliance disappoints &#124; Reuters |publisher=In.reuters.com |date= 2009-07-27|accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref> as well as tractors in India.\n\n==History==\nMahindra & Mahindra was incorporated as Muhammad & Mahindra in 1945 by the brothers [[J. C. Mahindra]] and [[K. C. Mahindra]] and [[Malik Ghulam Muhammad]] in [[Ludhiana]], [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]] to trade steel.  Following the [[Partition of India]] in 1947, Malik Ghulam Muhammad left the company and emigrated to [[Pakistan]] where he became the first finance minister of the new state (and later the third Governor General in 1951).  In 1948, K. C. Mahindra changed the company's name to [[Mahindra & Mahindra]].\n\nBuilding on their expertise in the [[steel industry]], the Mahindra brothers began trading steel with UK suppliers. They also won a contract to manufacture [[Willys Jeep]]s in India and began producing them in 1947. By 1956, the company was listed on the [[Bombay Stock Exchange]], and by 1969 the company had entered the world market as an exporter of [[utility vehicle]]s and spare parts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahindra.com/Heritage/milestonesyearwise.htm#1954 |title=Mahindra Corporate |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>  Like many Indian companies, Mahindra responded to the restrictions of the [[Licence Raj]] by expanding into other industries. Mahindra & Mahindra created a [[tractor]] division in 1982 and a tech division (now [[Tech Mahindra]]) in 1986. It has continued to diversify its operations ever since through both joint ventures and [[greenfield investment]]s.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/markets/india/article1945670.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Time to put Indias new business challenge on the road | first=Ashling | last=Oconnor | date=2007-06-18 | accessdate=2010-05-12}}</ref>\n\nBy 1994, the Group had become so diverse that it undertook a fundamental reorganization, dividing into six Strategic Business Units: [[Automotive]]; [[farm equipment|Farm Equipment]]; [[Infrastructure]]; [[Trade]] and [[Financial Services]]; [[Information Technology]]; and Automotive Components (known internally as Systech).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2006/0424/032_2.html |title=Putt-Putt Tractors, Revved-Up Goals |publisher=Forbes.com |date=2006-10-27 |accessdate=2010-08-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025180436/http://www.forbes.com/global/2006/0424/032_2.html |archive-date=25 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The new [[Managing Director]], [[Anand Mahindra]], followed this reorganization with a new logo in 2000 and the successful launch of the [[Mahindra Scorpio]] (a wholly indigenously designed vehicle) in 2002. Together with an overhaul in production and manufacturing methods, these changes helped make the company more competitive,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blonnet.com/2006/04/26/stories/2006042600141100.htm |title=The Hindu Business Line : Resurgent India strikes back with confidence |publisher=Blonnet.com |date=2006-04-26 |accessdate=2010-08-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060528134527/http://www.blonnet.com/2006/04/26/stories/2006042600141100.htm |archive-date=28 May 2006 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and since then the Group's reputation and revenues have risen noticeably. Currently, Mahindra & Mahindra is one of the 20 largest companies in India<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-the-top-20-companies-in-india/20101210.htm |title=The 20 Largest Companies in India |publisher=Rediff.com |date=2010-12-10 |accessdate=2011-02-18}}</ref> In 2009, Forbes ranked Mahindra among the top 200 most reputable companies in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/05/06/world-reputable-companies-leadership-reputation-table.html |title=World's Most Reputable Companies: The Rankings |publisher=Forbes.com |date=2009-05-06 |accessdate=2011-02-18}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, the Mahindra Group launched a new corporate brand, Mahindra Rise, to unify Mahindra's image across industries and geographies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-company/corporate-trends/mahindra-mahindra-to-use-rise-as-new-brand-positioning/articleshow/7304716.cms |title=Mahindra & Mahindra to use 'Rise' as new brand positioning |publisher=Economic Times |date=2011-01-17 |accessdate=2011-02-18}}</ref> The brand positions Mahindra products and services as aspirational, supporting customers' ambitions to 'Rise.'\n\nIn April 2012, the Mahindra Group showed interest in purchasing the bankrupt automobile company [[Saab Automobile|Saab]], and placed several bids for Saab, though was outbid by Saab's new owner [[National Electric Vehicle Sweden]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/international-business/Tata-Motors-places-bid-for-Saab-Automobile-Report/articleshow/12159611.cms |title=Tata Motors places bid for Saab Automobile: Report \u2013 The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2012-03-06 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Major business ventures==\n* '''Aerospace'''\n:* [[Mahindra Aerospace]]\n\n* '''Aftermarket'''\n:* Mahindra First Choice Services\n:* Mahindra First Choice Wheels\n\n* '''Agribusiness'''\n:* Mahindra Agribusiness Division\n:* EPC Mahindra\n\n* '''Automotive'''\n:* [[Mahindra & Mahindra]] \n:* [[Mahindra Truck and Bus Division|Mahindra Truck & Bus]]\n:* [[Mahindra Reva]]\n:* [[SsangYong Motor Company|SsangYong Motors]]\n:* [[Mahindra Two Wheelers]]\n:* [[GenZe (company)|GenZe]]\n:* [[Pininfarina]]\n:* [[Automobili Pininfarina]]\n:* [[Peugeot Motocycles]]\n:* [[Jawa Motocycles]]\n\n* '''Components'''\n:* Engines Engineering\n:* Mahindra Castings\n:* Mahindra Composites\n:* Mahindra Engineering\n:* Mahindra Gears and Transmissions\n:* Mahindra Forgings\n:* Mahindra Hinoday Ltd\n:* Mahindra Intertrade\n:* Mahindra Sona Ltd.\n:* Mahindra Steel Service Centre\n:* Mahindra Systech\n:*[[Mahindra Ugine Steel]]\n:* Metalcastello S.p.A\n\n* '''Consulting'''\n:* Mahindra Integrated Business Solutions\n:* Mahindra Consulting Engineers\n:* Mahindra Logisoft\n:* Mahindra Special Services Group\n\n* '''Defence'''\n:* Mahindra & Mahindra \u2013 Military Defence Division\n:* Defence Land Systems\n\n* '''Education'''\n:* [[Mahindra United World College of India]]\n:* [[Mahindra \u00c9cole Centrale]]\n\n* '''Energy'''\n:* Mahindra & Mahindra \u2013 Energy Division\n:* Mahindra Solar One\n:* [[Mahindra_Susten|Mahindra Susten Pvt. Ltd.]], formerly (Mahindra EPC Services Pvt. Ltd.)\n\n* '''Farm Equipment'''\n\n:* Mahindra & Mahindra \u2013 Farm Equipment Division\n:* Mahindra USA Inc\n:* Mahindra Yueda (Yancheng) Tractor Co\n:* [[Mahindra Tractors]]\n:* [[Erkunt Group|Erkunt Tractor]]\n:*[http://trakstartractor.com/about-us/ Gromax Agri Equipment Ltd.] (erstwhile [[Mahindra Gujarat Tractors Limited|Mahindra Gujarat Tractor Ltd]])\n:* [[Punjab Tractors Ltd.|Mahindra Swaraj]]\n:* [[Jiangling Tractors]]\n\n* '''Financial Services'''\n:* [[Mahindra & Mahindra Financial Services Limited]]\n:* Mahindra Insurance Brokers\n:* Mahindra Rural Housing Finance\n:* [[Mahindra Mutual Fund]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Sebi-grants-license-to-Mahindra-Mutual-Fund/articleshow/50876752.cms|title=Sebi grants license to Mahindra Mutual Fund|work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n* '''Hospitality'''\n:* [[Club Mahindra Holidays|Mahindra Holidays and Resorts]]\n\n* '''Industrial Equipment'''\n:* Mahindra Conveyor Systems\n\n* '''Information Technology'''\n:* [[Tech Mahindra]]\n:* [[Mahindra Comviva]]\n:* [[Bristlecone (company)|Bristlecone]]\n:* CanvasM\n\n* '''Logistics'''\n:* Mahindra Logistics\n:* Smart Shift\n\n* '''Luxury Boats'''\n:* Mahindra Marine Private Limited\n\n* '''Ecommerce'''\n:* M2ALL \u2013 Official Mahindra e-store\n<ref>https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/retail/with-m2all-launch-mahindra-forays-into-e-commerce/articleshow/48955235.cms?from=mdr</ref>\n<ref>https://www.zigwheels.com/news-features/news/mahindra-group-forays-into-ecommerce-with-m2all/23139/</ref>\n* '''Real Estate'''\n:* [[Mahindra Lifespaces]]\n:* [[Mahindra World City, New Chennai|Mahindra World City]]\n\n* '''Retail'''\n:* Mahindra Retail\n\n* '''Sports'''\n:* [[Mahindra United FC]]\n:* [[Mahindra Racing]]\n:* Mahindra-NBA Partnership\n:* Mahindra-Celtic Football Club Partnership\n\n* '''Defunct'''\n:* [[Mahindra Satyam]]\n:* [[Mahindra Renault Limited|Mahindra Renault]]\n\n==Community initiatives==\nThe Mahindra Group is extensively involved in [[philanthropy]] and volunteering.  It is considered an active participant in the Indian [[Corporate Social Responsibility]] field and received the Pegasus Award for CSR in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/india/news/pressmarket/mahindra-receives-pegasus-csr-award/18/40/317684|title=- Moneycontrol.com|date=17 December 2007|publisher=}}</ref>  Mahindra engages in philanthropy primarily through the KC Mahindra Trust, which serves as the CSR arm of the group (although many subsidiaries have their own CSR initiatives, notably [[Tech Mahindra]] and [[Mahindra Satyam]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/06/14/stories/2007061401871800.htm|title=Tech Mahindra launches foundation|work=The Hindu}}</ref>  Founded in 1953 by K.C Mahindra, the [[trust (law)|trust]] focuses primarily on fostering [[literacy in India]] and promoting higher learning through grants and scholarships.<ref>[http://www.nanhikali.org/aboutus/vision.aspx/ Project Nahni Kali Official Website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413161034/http://www.nanhikali.org/aboutus/vision.aspx |date=13 April 2009 }}</ref>  Mahindra operates several vocational schools as well as the [[Mahindra United World College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahindra.com/mahindra/how-we-help.page?cname=how-we-help&dname=Education |title=Education |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>  The KC Mahindra Trust\u2019s primary project however is [[Project Nanhi Kali]], which targets the education of young [[India]]n girls.<ref name=\"moneycontrol.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/india/news/pressmarket/mahindra-renews-its-commitment-to-society/16/00/305964|title=- Moneycontrol.com|date=3 October 2007|publisher=}}</ref> The foundation currently supports the education of approximately 51000 underprivileged girls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nanhikali.org/nanhikali/about_nanhi_kali.aspx|title=Nanhi Kali ::|publisher=}}</ref>  Other initiatives include Mahindra Hariyali (a 1 million tree planting campaign)<ref name=\"moneycontrol.com\"/> as well as sponsorship of the [[Lifeline Express]], a mobile hospital train.  Mahindra employees also plan and lead their own service projects through Mahindra\u2019s Employee Social Options Plans.  In 2009, more than 35,000 employees participated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mahindra.com/mahindra/how-we-help.page?cname=how-we-help&dname=Employee-Social-Options |title=how-we-help |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Mahindra Group was responsible for the creation of [[Mahindra United World College]], a [[United World Colleges|UWC]] campus located in [[Pune]].\n\nMahindra also supports the Mahindra Excellence in Theatre Awards to recognize Indian theater talent, the Mahindra Indo-American Film Festival, and the Mahindra Lucknow Festival.  In 2011, it held the first annual [[Mahindra Blues Festival]] with guests like Buddy Guy, Johnny Lang, and Shemekia Copeland at the [[Mehboob Studios]] in Mumbai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahindrablues.com |title=Alternative content |publisher=Mahindra Blues |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>  Mahindra also partners with the NBA and Celtic Football Club to bring grassroots basketball and football to India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mahindra.com/mahindra/how-we-help.page?cname=how-we-help&dname=Culture-and-Sports |title=how-we-help |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Leadership==\nKeshub Mahindra, the Chairman Emeritus of Mahindra & Mahindra, is a graduate of [[Wharton Business School]], [[University of Pennsylvania]], USA.  He joined the company in 1947 and became the chairman in 1963.\n\nDuring his career he  has also been Chairman of Bombay Chamber of Commerce and Industry (1966\u201367), President of ASSOCHAM (1969\u201370), Chairman of the [[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]] (1975\u201385); Member of the Foundation Board \u2013 [[International Institute for Management Development]] (1984\u201389)\n\nHis  awards include:\nCompanion \u2013 British Institute of Management(1985),\nChevalier de la L\u00e9gion d'honneur (1987),\nBusiness India \u2013 Businessman of the Year(1989),\nHonorary Fellowship of All India Management Association (1990),\nInstitute of Company Secretaries of India (ICSI) Lifetime Achievement Award for Excellence in Corporate Governance (2004),\nLakshya Business Visionary Award \u2013 NITIE (2006),\nICFAI Business School (IBS) Kolkata Lifetime Achievement Award presented by the Institute of Chartered Financial Analysts of India (ICFAI)(2007)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahindra.com/heritage/mfam_kcm.html |title=Mahindra Corporate |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of  the [[Bhopal Disaster]] he was managing director of Union Carbide India Ltd.( In 2010  he was charged and indicted for causing death due to negligence and sentenced to 2 years' imprisonment and Rs 1 Lakh fine. He was granted bail shortly after being sentenced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/06/07/2920596.htm |title=Eight convicted over Bhopal gas disaster \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Abc.net.au |date= |accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSSGE65607520100607?loomia_ow=t0:s0:a49:g43:r1:c0.188034:b34645298:z0 |title=UPDATE 2-Ex-Union Carbide officials jailed over Bhopal leak |publisher=Reuters |date= 2010-06-07|accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>\n\n[[Anand Mahindra]] is Chairman and Managing Director of Mahindra & Mahindra.  He graduated from [[Harvard University]] and earned his MBA from [[Harvard Business School]] in 1981.<ref name=AM-E-00>{{cite web|url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2010/10/harvard-humanities-2-0/|title=Harvard Humanities 2.0|work=Harvard Gazette}}</ref>  He joined the Mahindra Group in 1981 as an Executive Assistant to the Finance Director of the Mahindra Ugine Steel Company. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahindra.com/mahindra/who-we-are.page?cname=who-we-are&dname=Our-Leadership&scat=Anand-Mahindra |title=Anand Mahindra |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref> \n\n{|  class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\"\n| style=\"background:#f8eaba; text-align:center;\"|\n<div class=\"center\">\n; Mahindra Group's former logo\n</div>\n|-\n|\n<gallery>\nFile:Mahindra & Mahindra Logo.svg|\n</gallery>\n|-\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Club Mahindra Holidays]]\n* [[Mahindra & Mahindra]]\n* [[Tech Mahindra]]\n* [[Mahindra Aerospace]]\n{{Portalbar|companies}}\n\n==References==\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add references to this article, please see http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cite/Cite.php -->\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.mahindra.com}}\n\n{{Mahindra Group}}\n\n[[Category:Indian companies established in 1945]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies established in 1945]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of India]]\n[[Category:Indian brands]]\n[[Category:Mahindra Group]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{otheruses|Mahindra (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2016}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Mahindra Group\n| logo = [[File:Mahindra Rise New Logo.svg|200px]]\n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|df=yes|1945}}\n| founder = [[Jagdish Chandra Mahindra]]<br />[[Kailash Chandra Mahindra]]<br /> [[Malik Ghulam Muhammad]]\n| location = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = [[Anand Mahindra]] (Chairman & MD)<br />[[Keshub Mahindra]] (Chairman emeritus)\n| industry = [[Conglomerate (company)|Conglomerate]]\n| products = {{hlist | [[Automotive]]  | [[IT Services]] | [[Finance]]| [[Hospitality industry|Hospitality]] |[[Agribusiness]] | [[Defense (military)|Defense]] }}\n| revenue = {{profit}} [[United States dollar|US$]]20.7 billion (2018)<ref>{{cite web|title=Corporate overview|url=http://www.mahindra.com/about-us|date= | accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>\n| num_employees = 240,000 (2018)<ref name=Annual>[http://www.mahindra.com/Who-We-Are/Overview/ Employee strength]</ref>\n| subsid = [[Mahindra & Mahindra]],<br> [[SsangYong Motor Company|SsangYong Motors]],<br> [[Mahindra Aerospace]],<br>[[Mahindra & Mahindra Financial Services Limited]],<br> Mahindra Systech,<br> [[Tech Mahindra]],<br> [[Mahindra Lifespace Developers]],<br> Mahindra Ugine Steel Company <br>[[BSA Company]]\n[[Automobili Pininfarina]],<br>\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.mahindra.com/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Mahindra Group''' is an Indian multinational [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] [[holding company]] headquartered in [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]. It has operations in over 100 countries around the globe. The group has a presence in aerospace, agribusiness, aftermarket, automotive, components, construction equipment, defence, energy, farm equipment, finance and insurance, industrial equipment, information technology, leisure and hospitality, logistics, real estate, retail, and two wheelers.  It is considered to be one of the most reputable Indian industrial houses<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2006/11/20/leadership-companies-reputation-lead-managing-cx_hc_1120indarep_slide_9.html?thisSpeed=15000 |title=India's Most Reputable Companies |publisher=Forbes.com |date=2006-11-20 |accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref> with market leadership in utility vehicles<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/businessNews/idINIndia-41345620090727 |title=BSE Sensex little changed; Reliance disappoints &#124; Reuters |publisher=In.reuters.com |date= 2009-07-27|accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref> as well as tractors in India.\n\n==History==\nMahindra & Mahindra was incorporated as Muhammad & Mahindra in 1945 by the brothers [[J. C. Mahindra]] and [[K. C. Mahindra]] and [[Malik Ghulam Muhammad]] in [[Ludhiana]], [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]] to trade steel.  Following the [[Partition of India]] in 1947, Malik Ghulam Muhammad left the company and emigrated to [[Pakistan]] where he became the first finance minister of the new state (and later the third Governor General in 1951).  In 1948, K. C. Mahindra changed the company's name to [[Mahindra & Mahindra]].\n\nBuilding on their expertise in the [[steel industry]], the Mahindra brothers began trading steel with UK suppliers. They also won a contract to manufacture [[Willys Jeep]]s in India and began producing them in 1947. By 1956, the company was listed on the [[Bombay Stock Exchange]], and by 1969 the company had entered the world market as an exporter of [[utility vehicle]]s and spare parts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahindra.com/Heritage/milestonesyearwise.htm#1954 |title=Mahindra Corporate |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>  Like many Indian companies, Mahindra responded to the restrictions of the [[Licence Raj]] by expanding into other industries. Mahindra & Mahindra created a [[tractor]] division in 1982 and a tech division (now [[Tech Mahindra]]) in 1986. It has continued to diversify its operations ever since through both joint ventures and [[greenfield investment]]s.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/markets/india/article1945670.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Time to put Indias new business challenge on the road | first=Ashling | last=Oconnor | date=2007-06-18 | accessdate=2010-05-12}}</ref>\n\nBy 1994, the Group had become so diverse that it undertook a fundamental reorganization, dividing into six Strategic Business Units: [[Automotive]]; [[farm equipment|Farm Equipment]]; [[Infrastructure]]; [[Trade]] and [[Financial Services]]; [[Information Technology]]; and Automotive Components (known internally as Systech).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2006/0424/032_2.html |title=Putt-Putt Tractors, Revved-Up Goals |publisher=Forbes.com |date=2006-10-27 |accessdate=2010-08-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025180436/http://www.forbes.com/global/2006/0424/032_2.html |archive-date=25 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The new [[Managing Director]], [[Anand Mahindra]], followed this reorganization with a new logo in 2000 and the successful launch of the [[Mahindra Scorpio]] (a wholly indigenously designed vehicle) in 2002. Together with an overhaul in production and manufacturing methods, these changes helped make the company more competitive,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blonnet.com/2006/04/26/stories/2006042600141100.htm |title=The Hindu Business Line : Resurgent India strikes back with confidence |publisher=Blonnet.com |date=2006-04-26 |accessdate=2010-08-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060528134527/http://www.blonnet.com/2006/04/26/stories/2006042600141100.htm |archive-date=28 May 2006 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and since then the Group's reputation and revenues have risen noticeably. Currently, Mahindra & Mahindra is one of the 20 largest companies in India<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-the-top-20-companies-in-india/20101210.htm |title=The 20 Largest Companies in India |publisher=Rediff.com |date=2010-12-10 |accessdate=2011-02-18}}</ref> In 2009, Forbes ranked Mahindra among the top 200 most reputable companies in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/05/06/world-reputable-companies-leadership-reputation-table.html |title=World's Most Reputable Companies: The Rankings |publisher=Forbes.com |date=2009-05-06 |accessdate=2011-02-18}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, the Mahindra Group launched a new corporate brand, Mahindra Rise, to unify Mahindra's image across industries and geographies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-company/corporate-trends/mahindra-mahindra-to-use-rise-as-new-brand-positioning/articleshow/7304716.cms |title=Mahindra & Mahindra to use 'Rise' as new brand positioning |publisher=Economic Times |date=2011-01-17 |accessdate=2011-02-18}}</ref> The brand positions Mahindra products and services as aspirational, supporting customers' ambitions to 'Rise.'\n\nIn April 2012, the Mahindra Group showed interest in purchasing the bankrupt automobile company [[Saab Automobile|Saab]], and placed several bids for Saab, though was outbid by Saab's new owner [[National Electric Vehicle Sweden]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/international-business/Tata-Motors-places-bid-for-Saab-Automobile-Report/articleshow/12159611.cms |title=Tata Motors places bid for Saab Automobile: Report \u2013 The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2012-03-06 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Major business ventures==\n* '''Aerospace'''\n:* [[Mahindra Aerospace]]\n\n* '''Aftermarket'''\n:* Mahindra First Choice Services\n:* Mahindra First Choice Wheels\n\n* '''Agribusiness'''\n:* Mahindra Agribusiness Division\n:* EPC Mahindra\n\n* '''Automotive'''\n:* [[Mahindra & Mahindra]] \n:* Mahindra Truck & Bus\n:* [[Mahindra Reva]]\n:* [[SsangYong Motor Company|SsangYong Motors]]\n:* [[Mahindra Two Wheelers]]\n:* [[GenZe (company)|GenZe]]\n:* [[Pininfarina]]\n:* [[Automobili Pininfarina]]\n:* [[Peugeot Motocycles]]\n:* [[Jawa Motocycles]]\n\n* '''Components'''\n:* Engines Engineering\n:* Mahindra Castings\n:* Mahindra Composites\n:* Mahindra Engineering\n:* Mahindra Gears and Transmissions\n:* Mahindra Forgings\n:* Mahindra Hinoday Ltd\n:* Mahindra Intertrade\n:* Mahindra Sona Ltd.\n:* Mahindra Steel Service Centre\n:* Mahindra Systech\n:*[[Mahindra Ugine Steel]]\n:* Metalcastello S.p.A\n\n* '''Consulting'''\n:* Mahindra Integrated Business Solutions\n:* Mahindra Consulting Engineers\n:* Mahindra Logisoft\n:* Mahindra Special Services Group\n\n* '''Defence'''\n:* Mahindra & Mahindra \u2013 Military Defence Division\n:* Defence Land Systems\n\n* '''Education'''\n:* [[Mahindra United World College of India]]\n:* [[Mahindra \u00c9cole Centrale]]\n\n* '''Energy'''\n:* Mahindra & Mahindra \u2013 Energy Division\n:* Mahindra Solar One\n:* [[Mahindra_Susten|Mahindra Susten Pvt. Ltd.]], formerly (Mahindra EPC Services Pvt. Ltd.)\n\n* '''Farm Equipment'''\n\n:* Mahindra & Mahindra \u2013 Farm Equipment Division\n:* Mahindra USA Inc\n:* Mahindra Yueda (Yancheng) Tractor Co\n:* [[Mahindra Tractors]]\n:* [[Erkunt Group|Erkunt Tractor]]\n:*[http://trakstartractor.com/about-us/ Gromax Agri Equipment Ltd.] (erstwhile [[Mahindra Gujarat Tractors Limited|Mahindra Gujarat Tractor Ltd]])\n:* [[Punjab Tractors Ltd.|Mahindra Swaraj]]\n:* [[Jiangling Tractors]]\n\n* '''Financial Services'''\n:* [[Mahindra & Mahindra Financial Services Limited]]\n:* Mahindra Insurance Brokers\n:* Mahindra Rural Housing Finance\n:* [[Mahindra Mutual Fund]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Sebi-grants-license-to-Mahindra-Mutual-Fund/articleshow/50876752.cms|title=Sebi grants license to Mahindra Mutual Fund|work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n* '''Hospitality'''\n:* [[Club Mahindra Holidays|Mahindra Holidays and Resorts]]\n\n* '''Industrial Equipment'''\n:* Mahindra Conveyor Systems\n\n* '''Information Technology'''\n:* [[Tech Mahindra]]\n:* [[Mahindra Comviva]]\n:* [[Bristlecone (company)|Bristlecone]]\n:* CanvasM\n\n* '''Logistics'''\n:* Mahindra Logistics\n:* Smart Shift\n\n* '''Luxury Boats'''\n:* Mahindra Marine Private Limited\n\n* '''Ecommerce'''\n:* M2ALL \u2013 Official Mahindra e-store\n<ref>https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/retail/with-m2all-launch-mahindra-forays-into-e-commerce/articleshow/48955235.cms?from=mdr</ref>\n<ref>https://www.zigwheels.com/news-features/news/mahindra-group-forays-into-ecommerce-with-m2all/23139/</ref>\n* '''Real Estate'''\n:* [[Mahindra Lifespaces]]\n:* [[Mahindra World City, New Chennai|Mahindra World City]]\n\n* '''Retail'''\n:* Mahindra Retail\n\n* '''Sports'''\n:* [[Mahindra United FC]]\n:* [[Mahindra Racing]]\n:* Mahindra-NBA Partnership\n:* Mahindra-Celtic Football Club Partnership\n\n* '''Defunct'''\n:* [[Mahindra Satyam]]\n:* [[Mahindra Renault Limited|Mahindra Renault]]\n\n==Community initiatives==\nThe Mahindra Group is extensively involved in [[philanthropy]] and volunteering.  It is considered an active participant in the Indian [[Corporate Social Responsibility]] field and received the Pegasus Award for CSR in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/india/news/pressmarket/mahindra-receives-pegasus-csr-award/18/40/317684|title=- Moneycontrol.com|date=17 December 2007|publisher=}}</ref>  Mahindra engages in philanthropy primarily through the KC Mahindra Trust, which serves as the CSR arm of the group (although many subsidiaries have their own CSR initiatives, notably [[Tech Mahindra]] and [[Mahindra Satyam]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/06/14/stories/2007061401871800.htm|title=Tech Mahindra launches foundation|work=The Hindu}}</ref>  Founded in 1953 by K.C Mahindra, the [[trust (law)|trust]] focuses primarily on fostering [[literacy in India]] and promoting higher learning through grants and scholarships.<ref>[http://www.nanhikali.org/aboutus/vision.aspx/ Project Nahni Kali Official Website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413161034/http://www.nanhikali.org/aboutus/vision.aspx |date=13 April 2009 }}</ref>  Mahindra operates several vocational schools as well as the [[Mahindra United World College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahindra.com/mahindra/how-we-help.page?cname=how-we-help&dname=Education |title=Education |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>  The KC Mahindra Trust\u2019s primary project however is [[Project Nanhi Kali]], which targets the education of young [[India]]n girls.<ref name=\"moneycontrol.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/india/news/pressmarket/mahindra-renews-its-commitment-to-society/16/00/305964|title=- Moneycontrol.com|date=3 October 2007|publisher=}}</ref> The foundation currently supports the education of approximately 51000 underprivileged girls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nanhikali.org/nanhikali/about_nanhi_kali.aspx|title=Nanhi Kali ::|publisher=}}</ref>  Other initiatives include Mahindra Hariyali (a 1 million tree planting campaign)<ref name=\"moneycontrol.com\"/> as well as sponsorship of the [[Lifeline Express]], a mobile hospital train.  Mahindra employees also plan and lead their own service projects through Mahindra\u2019s Employee Social Options Plans.  In 2009, more than 35,000 employees participated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mahindra.com/mahindra/how-we-help.page?cname=how-we-help&dname=Employee-Social-Options |title=how-we-help |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Mahindra Group was responsible for the creation of [[Mahindra United World College]], a [[United World Colleges|UWC]] campus located in [[Pune]].\n\nMahindra also supports the Mahindra Excellence in Theatre Awards to recognize Indian theater talent, the Mahindra Indo-American Film Festival, and the Mahindra Lucknow Festival.  In 2011, it held the first annual [[Mahindra Blues Festival]] with guests like Buddy Guy, Johnny Lang, and Shemekia Copeland at the [[Mehboob Studios]] in Mumbai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahindrablues.com |title=Alternative content |publisher=Mahindra Blues |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>  Mahindra also partners with the NBA and Celtic Football Club to bring grassroots basketball and football to India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mahindra.com/mahindra/how-we-help.page?cname=how-we-help&dname=Culture-and-Sports |title=how-we-help |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Leadership==\nKeshub Mahindra, the Chairman Emeritus of Mahindra & Mahindra, is a graduate of [[Wharton Business School]], [[University of Pennsylvania]], USA.  He joined the company in 1947 and became the chairman in 1963.\n\nDuring his career he  has also been Chairman of Bombay Chamber of Commerce and Industry (1966\u201367), President of ASSOCHAM (1969\u201370), Chairman of the [[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]] (1975\u201385); Member of the Foundation Board \u2013 [[International Institute for Management Development]] (1984\u201389)\n\nHis  awards include:\nCompanion \u2013 British Institute of Management(1985),\nChevalier de la L\u00e9gion d'honneur (1987),\nBusiness India \u2013 Businessman of the Year(1989),\nHonorary Fellowship of All India Management Association (1990),\nInstitute of Company Secretaries of India (ICSI) Lifetime Achievement Award for Excellence in Corporate Governance (2004),\nLakshya Business Visionary Award \u2013 NITIE (2006),\nICFAI Business School (IBS) Kolkata Lifetime Achievement Award presented by the Institute of Chartered Financial Analysts of India (ICFAI)(2007)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahindra.com/heritage/mfam_kcm.html |title=Mahindra Corporate |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of  the [[Bhopal Disaster]] he was managing director of Union Carbide India Ltd.( In 2010  he was charged and indicted for causing death due to negligence and sentenced to 2 years' imprisonment and Rs 1 Lakh fine. He was granted bail shortly after being sentenced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/06/07/2920596.htm |title=Eight convicted over Bhopal gas disaster \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Abc.net.au |date= |accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSSGE65607520100607?loomia_ow=t0:s0:a49:g43:r1:c0.188034:b34645298:z0 |title=UPDATE 2-Ex-Union Carbide officials jailed over Bhopal leak |publisher=Reuters |date= 2010-06-07|accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>\n\n[[Anand Mahindra]] is Chairman and Managing Director of Mahindra & Mahindra.  He graduated from [[Harvard University]] and earned his MBA from [[Harvard Business School]] in 1981.<ref name=AM-E-00>{{cite web|url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2010/10/harvard-humanities-2-0/|title=Harvard Humanities 2.0|work=Harvard Gazette}}</ref>  He joined the Mahindra Group in 1981 as an Executive Assistant to the Finance Director of the Mahindra Ugine Steel Company. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahindra.com/mahindra/who-we-are.page?cname=who-we-are&dname=Our-Leadership&scat=Anand-Mahindra |title=Anand Mahindra |publisher=Mahindra.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref> \n\n{|  class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\"\n| style=\"background:#f8eaba; text-align:center;\"|\n<div class=\"center\">\n; Mahindra Group's former logo\n</div>\n|-\n|\n<gallery>\nFile:Mahindra & Mahindra Logo.svg|\n</gallery>\n|-\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Club Mahindra Holidays]]\n* [[Mahindra & Mahindra]]\n* [[Tech Mahindra]]\n* [[Mahindra Aerospace]]\n{{Portalbar|companies}}\n\n==References==\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add references to this article, please see http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cite/Cite.php -->\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.mahindra.com}}\n\n{{Mahindra Group}}\n\n[[Category:Indian companies established in 1945]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies established in 1945]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of India]]\n[[Category:Indian brands]]\n[[Category:Mahindra Group]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in India]]\n", "name_user": "Carsmaniac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added missing link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahindra_Group"}
{"title_page": "Kalki", "text_new": "Kalki means kalghi \n\nkalki avtaar ho Gaya h kalghidhar shri guru Gobind singh ke Roop Mai .\n<br />{{short description|tenth incarnation of Vishnu in Hinduism}}\n{{other uses|Kalki (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox deity<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Hindu mythology-->\n| type        = Hindu\n| name        = Kalki\n| image       =Kalki Avatar by Ravi Varma.jpg\n| caption     = Kalki Avatar by [[Raja Ravi Varma]]\n| deity_of    = The tenth avatar of Vishnu\n| Devanagari  = \u0915\u0932\u094d\u0915\u093f  \t\n| Sanskrit_transliteration = Kalki\t \t\n| texts        = Hinduism: ''[[Mahabharat]]''<br/>''[[Puranas]]''<br>Buddhism: ''[[Kalachakra]]-Tantra''\n| mount       = Devadatta (i.e. [[White horse (mythology)#Hindu|White horse]])<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\"/><ref name=\"Dalal2010p188\">{{harvnb|Dalal|2014|p=188}}</ref> \t\n}}\n'''Kalki''', also called '''Kalkin''' or '''Karki''',<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\">{{cite book|author=J. L. Brockington|title=The Sanskrit Epics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HR-_LK5kl18C&pg=PA287 |year=1998|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-10260-4|pages=287\u2013288 with footnotes 126\u2013127}}</ref> is the tenth [[avatar]] of Hindu god [[Vishnu]] to end the [[Kali Yuga]], one of the four periods in the endless cycle of existence (''krita'') in [[Vaishnavism]] cosmology. He is described in the Puranas as the avatar who rejuvenates existence by ending the darkest and destructive period to remove [[adharma]] and ushering in the [[Satya Yuga]], while riding a white horse with a fiery sword.<ref name=\"Dalal2010p188\"/> The description and details of Kalki are inconsistent among the Puranic texts. He is, for example, only an invisible force destroying evil and chaos in some texts {{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}, while an actual person who kills those who persecute others, and portrayed as someone leading an army of dharmic warriors in some. \n\nKalki is also found in Buddhist texts. In [[Tibetan Buddhism]], the ''[[Kalachakra]]-Tantra'<ref name=\"Lopez2015p202\"/><ref name=\"Perry2017p220\"/><ref name=\"Dahla2006p90\"/>\n\nThe prophecy of Kalki avatar is believed by the followers of [[Vaishnavism]] sect of hinduism, as a part of the ten avatars of [[Vishnu]], who is cheif deity in vaishnavism. The [[Shaivism]] and [[Shaktism]] sects of hinduism may or may not believe in this prophecy, because Vishnu is not the cheif deity in those sects. \n\n\n\nAfter Kalki new yug known as Satyug will start.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name Kalki is derived based ''Kal'', which means \"time\" ([[kali yuga]]).<ref name=\"Klostermaier2006p75\">{{cite book|author=Klaus K. Klostermaier|title=Mythologies and Philosophies of Salvation in the Theistic Traditions of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CFQ9DgAAQBAJ |year=2006|publisher=Wilfrid Laurier Univ. Press|isbn=978-0-88920-743-1|page=75}}</ref> The literal meaning of Kalki is \"dirty, sinful\", which Brockington states does not make sense in the avatara context.<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\"/> This has led scholars such as Otto Schrader to suggest that the original term may have been ''karki'' (white, from the horse) which morphed into Kalki. This proposal is supported by two versions of ''Mahabharata'' manuscripts (e.g. the G3.6 manuscript) that have been found, where the Sanskrit verses name the avatar to be \"karki\", rather than \"kalki\".<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\" />\n\n==Description==\n{{Vaishnavism}}\nKalki is an avatara of Vishnu. Avatara means \"descent\" and refers to a descent of the divine into the material realm of human existence. The [[Garuda Purana]] lists [[Dasavatara of Vishnu#List|ten avatars]], with Kalki being the tenth.<ref>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|url=https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada|last=Gopal|first=Madan|year= 1990| page= [https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada/page/73 73]|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref> He is described as the avatar who appears at the end of the Kali Yuga. He ends the darkest, degenerating and chaotic stage of the Kali ''Yuga'' (period) to remove [[adharma]] and ushers in the [[Satya Yuga]], while riding a white horse with a fiery sword.<ref name=\"Dalal2010p188\"/><ref name=\"Doniger1999p629\">{{cite book| author1=Wendy Doniger|author2=Merriam-Webster, Inc|title=Merriam-Webster's Encyclopedia of World Religions| url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780877790440 | url-access=registration|year=1999|publisher=Merriam-Webster|isbn=978-0-87779-044-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780877790440/page/659 659]}}</ref> He restarts a new cycle of time.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ludo Rocher|editor=Ralph M. Rosen|title=Time and Temporality in the Ancient World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=It9KMklf4R4C&pg=PA91|date=22 March 2004|publisher=UPenn Museum of Archaeology|isbn=978-1-931707-67-1|pages=91\u201393}}</ref> He is described as a warrior in the Puranas.<ref name=\"Dalal2010p188\"/><ref name=\"Doniger1999p629\"/>\n\n===Wheel of Time Tantra===\nIn the Buddhist text ''Kalachakra Tantra'', the righteous kings are called Kalki (Kalkin, lit. chieftain) living in Sambhala. There are many Kalki in this text, each fighting barbarism, persecution and chaos. The last Kalki is called \"Cakrin\" and is predicted to end the chaos and degeneration by assembling a large army to eradicate the \"forces of Evil\".<ref name=\"Lopez2015p202\"/><ref name=\"Perry2017p220\"/> A great war and Armageddon will destroy the barbaric forces, states the text.<ref name=\"Lopez2015p202\"/><ref name=\"Perry2017p220\"/><ref name=\"Dahla2006p90\">[a] {{cite book|author=Bj\u00f6rn Dahla|title=Exercising Power: The Role of Religions in Concord and Conflict|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i_rWAAAAMAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Donner Institute for Research in Religious and Cultural History|isbn=978-952-12-1811-8|pages=90\u201391}}, '''Quote:''' \"(...) the Shambala-bodhisattva-king [Cakravartin Kalkin] and his army will defeat and destroy the enemy army.\";<br>[b] {{cite book|author=David Burton|title=Buddhism: A Contemporary Philosophical Investigation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=phddDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT193 |year=2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-83859-7|page=193}}<br>[c] {{cite book|author=Johan Elverskog |editor=Anna Akasoy|display-editors=etal|title=Islam and Tibet: Interactions Along the Musk Routes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZfWXIfbynwYC&pg=PA293 |year=2011|publisher=Ashgate Publishing |isbn=978-0-7546-6956-2|pages=293\u2013310}}</ref> According to Donald Lopez \u2013 a professor of Buddhist Studies, Kalki is predicted to start the new cycle of perfect era where \"People will live long, happy lives and righteousness will reign supreme\".<ref name=\"Lopez2015p202\"/> The text is significant in establishing the chronology of the Kalki idea to be from post-7th century, probably the 9th or 10th century.<ref name=\"JIN2017p49\">{{cite book|author=Yijiu JIN|title=Islam|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q-PzDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA49|year=2017|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=978-90-474-2800-8|pages=49\u201352}}</ref> Lopez states that the Buddhist text likely borrowed it from Hindu mythology.<ref name=\"Lopez2015p202\">{{cite book|author=Donald S. Lopez Jr.|title=Buddhism in Practice |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zaC4CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA202 |year=2015|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-8007-2|pages=202\u2013204}}</ref><ref name=\"Perry2017p220\">{{cite book|author=Perry Schmidt-Leukel|title=Religious Pluralism and Interreligious Theology: The Gifford Lectures |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ir3zDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT221 |year=2017|publisher=Orbis|isbn=978-1-60833-695-1|pages=220\u2013222}}</ref> Other scholars, such as Yijiu Jin, state that the text originated in Central Asia in the 10th-century, and Tibetan literature picked up a version of it in India around 1027 CE.<ref name=\"JIN2017p49\"/>\n\n==Development  ==\nThere is no mention of Kalki in the [[Vedas|Vedic]] literature.<ref name=academy81>{{cite book|title=Tattvad\u012bpa\u1e25: Journal of Academy of Sanskrit Research, Volume 5|page=81|publisher=The Academy|year=2001|quote=Kalki, as an incarnation of Visnu, is not found in the Vedic literature. But some of the features of that concept, viz., the fearful elements, the epithet Kalmallkinam (brilliant, remover of darkness) of Rudra, prompt us to admit him as the forerunner of Kalki.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Rabiprasad Mishra|title=Theory of Incarnation: Its Origin and Development in the Light of Vedic and Pur\u0101\u1e47ic References|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3XvXAAAAMAAJ |year=2000|publisher=Pratibha |isbn=978-81-7702-021-2|page=146}}, Quote: \"Kalki as an incarnation of Visnu is not mentioned in the Vedic literature.\"</ref> The epithet \"Kalmallkinam\", meaning \"brilliant remover of darkness\", is found in the Vedic literature for [[Rudra]] (later Shiva), which has been interpreted to be \"forerunner of Kalki\".<ref name=academy81/>\n\nKalki appears for the first time in the great war epic ''Mahabharata''.<ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2011p104\">{{cite book|author=Alf Hiltebeitel|title=Reading the Fifth Veda: Studies on the Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata - Essays by Alf Hiltebeitel|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=lLfHSOWKB-sC&pg=PA531|year=2011|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=978-90-04-18566-1|pages=89\u2013110, 530\u2013531}}</ref> The mention of Kalki in the ''Mahabharata'' occurs only once, over the verses 3.188.85\u20133.189.6.<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\"/> The Kalki avatar is found in the Maha-Puranas such as ''[[Vishnu Purana]]'',<ref>{{cite book |last=Wilson |first=Horace |authorlink=Horace Hayman Wilson |title=Vishnu Purana |year=2001 |publisher=Ganesha Publishing |isbn=1-86210-016-0 |page=72}}</ref> ''[[Matsya Purana]]'', and ''[[Bhagavata Purana]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Theory of Avat\u0101ra and Divinity of Chaitanya|first=Janmajit|last=Roy|page=39 |publisher = Atlantic Publishers}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Myths and Gods of India: The Classic Work on Hindu Polytheism from the Princeton Bollingen Series|first=Alain|last=Dani\u00e9lou|page=181|publisher=Inner Traditions / Bear & Co}}</ref> However, the details relating the Kalki mythologies are divergent between the Epic and the Puranas, as well as within the Puranas.<ref name=\"Mitchiner2000p68\">{{cite book|author=John E. Mitchiner|title=Traditions Of The Seven Rsis|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=phGzVwTTp_gC|year= 2000|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass |isbn= 978-81-208-1324-3|pages= 68\u201369 with footnotes}}</ref><ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2011p104\"/>\n\nIn the ''Mahabharata'', according to Hiltebeitel, Kalki is an extension of the [[Parasurama]] avatar legend warrior destroys those kings who were abusing their power to spread chaos, evil and persecution of the powerless. The Epic character of Kalki restores dharma, restores justice in the world, but does not end the cycle of existence.<ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2011p104\"/><ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2011p288\">{{cite book|author=Alf Hiltebeitel|title=Dharma: Its Early History in Law, Religion, and Narrative|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U4NF8pYxdvIC |year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-539423-8|pages=288\u2013292}}</ref> The Kalkin section in the ''Mahabharata'' occurs in the Markandeya section. There, states Luis Reimann, can \"hardly be any doubt that the Markandeya section is a late addition to the Epic. Making Yudhisthira ask a question about conditions at the end of Kali and the beginning of Krta \u2014 something far removed from his own situation \u2014 is merely a device for justifying the inclusion of this subject matter in the Epic.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Luis Gonz\u00e1lez Reimann|title=The Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata and the Yugas: India's Great Epic Poem and the Hindu System of World Ages|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=nXrXAAAAMAAJ|year =2002|publisher= Peter Lang|isbn= 978-0-8204-5530-3|pages= 89\u201399, quote is on page 97}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Cornelia Dimmitt, the \"clear and tidy\" systematization of Kalki and the remaining nine avatars of Vishnu is not found in any of the Maha-Puranas.<ref name=\"Dimmitt2012p63\"/> The coverage of Kalki in these Hindu texts is scant, in contrast to the legends of Matsya, Kurma, Varaha, Vamana, Narasimha and Krishna, all of which are repeatedly and extensively described. According to Dimmitt, this was likely because just like the concept of the Buddha as a Vishnu avatar, the concept of Kalki was \"somewhat in flux\" when the major Puranas were being compiled.<ref name=\"Dimmitt2012p63\"/><ref name=\"Dimmitt2012p63\">{{harvnb|Dimmitt|van Buitenen|2012|pp=63\u201364}}</ref>\n\nThis myth may have developed in the Hindu texts both as a reaction to the invasions of the Indian subcontinent by various armies over the centuries from its northwest, and the mythologies these invaders brought with them.<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\"/><ref name=\"Doniger2004p235\">{{cite book|author=Wendy Doniger|title=Hindu Myths: A Sourcebook Translated from the Sanskrit|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQ4IMQAACAAJ |year=2004 |publisher =Penguin Books |isbn=978-0-14-044990-7|pages=235\u2013237}}</ref>\n\nAccording to John Mitchiner, the Kalki concept was likely borrowed \"in some measure from similar Jewish, Christian, Zoroastrian and other religions\".<ref name=\"Mitchiner2000p75\">{{cite book|author=John E. Mitchiner|title=Traditions Of The Seven Rsis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=phGzVwTTp_gC |year=2000|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1324-3|pages=75\u201376}}</ref> Mitchiner states that some Puranas such as the Yuga Purana do not mention Kalki and offer a different cosmology than the other Puranas. The Yuga Purana mythologizes in greater details the post-Maurya era Indo-Greek and Saka era, while the Manvantara theme containing the Kalki idea is mythologized greater in other Puranas.<ref name=\"Mitchiner2000p69\">{{cite book|author=John E. Mitchiner|title=Traditions Of The Seven Rsis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=phGzVwTTp_gC |year=2000|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1324-3|pages=69\u201376}}</ref><ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2011p104\" /> Luis Gonzales-Reimann concurs with Mitchiner, stating that the Yuga Purana does not mention Kalki.<ref name=\"Reimann2002p95\">{{cite book|author=Luis Gonz\u00e1lez-Reimann|title=The Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata and the Yugas: India's Great Epic Poem and the Hindu System of World Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nXrXAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-0-8204-5530-3|pages=95\u201399 }}</ref> In other texts such as the sections 2.36 and 2.37 of the Vayu Purana, states Reimann, it is not Kalkin who ends the Kali Yuga, but a different character named Pramiti.<ref name=\"Reimann2002p112\">{{cite book|author=Luis Gonz\u00e1lez Reimann|title=The Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata and the Yugas: India's Great Epic Poem and the Hindu System of World Ages|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=nXrXAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-0-8204-5530-3|pages=112\u2013113 note 39}}; Note: Reimann mentions some attempts to \"identify both Pramiti and Kalkin with historical rulers\".</ref> Most historians, states Arvind Sharma, link the development of Kalki mythology in Hinduism to the suffering caused by foreign invasions.<ref name=\"Sharma2012p244\">{{cite book|author=Arvind Sharma|title=Religious Studies and Comparative Methodology: The Case for Reciprocal Illumination|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CfZ9y5-FGPgC |year=2012|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-8325-1|pages=244\u2013245}}</ref>\n\n===Kalki Purana===\nA minor text named [[Kalki Purana]] is a relatively recent text, likely composed in [[Bengal]]. Its dating [[floruit]] is the 18th-century.{{sfn|Rocher|1986|p=183 with footnotes}} Wendy Doniger dates the Kalki mythology containing ''Kalki Purana'' to between 1500 and 1700 CE.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wendy Doniger|title=Textual Sources for the Study of Hinduism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KtZRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA5 |year=1988|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0-7190-1867-1|page=5}}</ref>\n\nIn the ''Kalki Purana'', Kalki marries princess Padmavati, the daughter of Brhadratha of Simhala.{{sfn|Rocher|1986|p=183 with footnotes}} He fights an evil army and many wars, ends evil but does not end existence. Kalki returns to Sambhala, inaugurates a new ''[[yuga]]'' for the good and then goes to heaven.{{sfn|Rocher|1986|p=183 with footnotes}}\n\n==Kalki Avatar in Sikhism==\n\n[[File:Kalki Avatar.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Kalki Avatar Punjab Hills, Guler, c. 1765.]]\n\nThe Kalki avatar appears in the historic [[Sikh]] texts, most notably in [[Dasam Granth]] as Nihakalanki, a text that is traditionally attributed to [[Guru Gobind Singh]].<ref name=\"Rinehart2011p29\">{{cite book|author=Robin Rinehart|title=Debating the Dasam Granth|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=58AVDAAAQBAJ |year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-975506-6|pages=29\u201330}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=W. H. McLeod|title=Sikhs of the Khalsa: A History of the Khalsa Rahit|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HIrXAAAAMAAJ |year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-565916-0|pages=149\u2013150}}</ref> The ''Chaubis Avatar'' (24 avatars) section mentions sage Matsyanra describing the appearance of Vishnu avatars to fight evil, greed, violence and ignorance. It includes Kalki as the twenty-fourth incarnation to lead the war between the forces of righteousness and unrighteousness, states Dhavan.<ref>{{cite book|author=Purnima Dhavan|title=When Sparrows Became Hawks: The Making of the Sikh Warrior Tradition, 1699-1799|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-7HJ5idB8_QC |year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-975655-1|pages=1 55\u2013157, 186 note 32}}</ref>\n\n==Features and iconography==\n[[File:Kalki_avatar_idol_in_rani_ki_vav_patan.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Statue Of god Kalki Avatar on wall of [[Rani ki vav|Rani Ki Vav]] (The Queens Stepwell) at Patan [[Gujarat]], [[India]]]]\n[Lord [[Shiva]] said to Lord Kalki:] \"This '''horse''' was manifested from [[Garuda]], and it can go anywhere at will and assume many different forms. Here also is a '''parrot''' [ [[Shuka]] ] that knows everything - past, present, and future. I would like to offer You both the horse and the parrot and so please accept them. By the influence of this horse and parrot, the people of the world will know You as a learned scholar of all scriptures who is a master of the art of releasing arrows, and thus the conqueror of all. I would also like to present You this sharp, strong '''sword''' and so please accept it. The handle of this sword is bedecked with jewels, and it is extremely powerful. As such, the sword will help You to reduce the heavy burden of the earth.\"<ref>Bhumipati Das. ''Sri Kalki Purana''. 2nd ed. India: Jai Nitai Press, 2011. pp. 33\u201334 (ch 3, text 25\u201327).</ref>\n\nThereafter, Lord Kalki picked up His brightly shining '''trident''' and '''bow and arrows''' and set out from His palace, riding upon His victorious horse and wearing His '''amulet'''.<ref>Bhumipati Das. ''Sri Kalki Purana''. 2nd ed. India: Jai Nitai Press, 2011. p. 36 (ch 3, text 36).</ref>\n\n[Shuka said to Padmavati:] [Lord Kalki] received a sword, horse, parrot, and '''shield''' from [[Shiva|Mahadeva]], as a benediction.<ref>Bhumipati Das. ''Sri Kalki Purana''. 2nd ed. India: Jai Nitai Press, 2011. p. 84 (ch 8, text 24).</ref>\n\n==Predictions about birth and arrival==\n\nIn the cyclic concept of time (''Puranic Kalpa''), [[Kaliyuga]] is variously estimated to last between 400,000 and 432,000 years. In some Vaishnava texts, Kalki is forecasted to appear on a white horse, at the end of Kaliyuga, to end the age of degeneration and to restore virtue and world order.<ref name=\"coulter2013\"/><ref name=\"Oxford University Press\">{{cite book|title=The Oxford Handbook of New Religious Movements, Volume 2|author1=James R. Lewis|author2=Inga B. Tollefsen|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=488}}</ref>\n\nKalki is described differently in Indian and non-Indian Buddhist manuscripts. The Indian texts state that Kalki will be born to Awejsirdenee and Bishenjun,<ref name=coulter2013/> or alternatively in the family of Sumati and Vishnuyasha.<ref name=\"emperor\"/>{{sfn|Rocher|1986|p=183}} He appears at the end of Kali Yuga to restore the order of the world.<ref name=coulter2013>{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Ancient Deities|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VWxekbhM1yEC|author1=Charles Russell Coulter|author2=Patricia Turner|publisher=Routledge|year=2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Oxford University Press\"/> Vishnuyasha is stated to be a prominent headman of the village called [[Shambhala]]. He will become the king, a \"Turner of the Wheel\", and one who triumphs. He will eliminate all barbarians and robbers, end ''adharma'', restart ''dharma'', and save the good people.<ref name=\"incarnation\">{{cite book|title=The Mahabharata, Volume 2: Book 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GfhJCgAAQBAJ|page=597\u2013598|year=1987|publisher=University of Chicago Press|author=J.A.B. van Buitenen}}</ref> After that, humanity will be transformed and will prevail on earth, and the golden age will begin.<ref name=\"incarnation\"/>\n\nIn the Kanchipuram temple, two relief Puranic panels depict Kalki, one relating to lunar (daughter-based) dynasty as mother of Kalki and another to solar (son-based) dynasty as father of Kalki.<ref name=\"emperor\"/> In these panels, states D Dennis Hudson, the story depicted is in terms of Kalki fighting and defeating asura [[Kali (demon)|Kali]]. He rides a white horse called Devadatta, ends evil, purifies everyone's minds and consciousness, and heralds the start of Krita Yuga.<ref name=\"emperor\">{{cite book|title=The Body of God: An Emperor's Palace for Krishna in Eighth-Century Kanchipuram|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2008|author=D Dennis Hudson|pages=333\u2013340}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dasavatar, 19th century.jpg|thumb|center|650px|19th-century [[Dashavatara]] painting (from left): Matsya, Kurma, Varaha, Narasimha, Vamana, Parashurama, Rama, Krishna, Buddha and Kalki.]]\n\n==People who claimed to be Kalki==\nList of people who have claimed to be the Kalki avatar:\n*[[Mirza Ghulam Ahmad]], founder of [[Ahmadiyya]] movement, claimed to be the Kalki Avatar, as well as [[Mahdi]].<ref>{{cite book | title = Oxford Handbook of Global Religions | first = Mark | last = Juergensmeyer | publisher =Oxford University Press | location = Oxford | year = 2006 | page = 520 | id = , ISBN (Ten digit): 0195137981| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lQMurMhRtfIC&pg=PA520| isbn = 978-0-19-513798-9 }}</ref>\n*In the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]], [[Bah\u00e1'u'll\u00e1h]] is identified as Kalki as well as the prophesied redeeming God at the end of the world, as claimed in Babism, Islam (Mahdi), Christianity (Messiah) and Buddhism (Maitreya).<ref name=\"Bassuk1987p146\">{{cite book|author=Daniel E Bassuk|title=Incarnation in Hinduism and Christianity: The Myth of the God-Man|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k3iwCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA146 |year=1987|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-1-349-08642-9|pages=146\u2013147}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=John M. Robertson|title=Tough Guys and True Believers: Managing Authoritarian Men in the Psychotherapy Room |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fTiZY_5wlJ4C&pg=PA62 |year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-81774-8|pages=62\u201363}}</ref>\n* Various [[Shia Muslim]] missionaries in South Asia \u2013 such as Siddiq Hussain \u2013 seeking to convert Hindus to their sect of Islam; they either claimed themselves to be Kalki, or claimed that \"all\" the [[The Twelve Imams|Shia Imams]] were Kalki, or claimed [[Muhammad]] was Kalki.<ref>{{cite book | last=Robinson | first=R. | last2=Clarke | first2=S. | title=Religious Conversion in India: Modes, Motivations, and Meanings | publisher=Oxford University Press | year=2003 | isbn=978-0-19-566329-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eNsoAAAAYAAJ | pages=44,108\u2013113}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Sikand | first=Y. | title=Muslims in India Since 1947: Islamic Perspectives on Inter-Faith Relations | publisher=Taylor & Francis | year=2004 | isbn=978-1-134-37825-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yf5aJi2loLcC  | pages=162\u2013171}}</ref>\n*[[Sri Bhagavan]], of Golden Age Foundation, Bhagavad Dharma, Kalki Dharma and the [[Oneness organisation|Oneness Organisation]], born on 7 March 1949.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KisRDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT488 The Oxford Handbook of New Religious Movements, Volume 2], p.488, James R. Lewis, Inga B. Tollefsen, Oxford University Press</ref>\n*[[Samael Aun Weor]], founder of the Universal Christian Gnostic Movement.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who is Samael Aun Weor?|url=http://www.samael.org/idiomas/ingles/paginas/1_quien_samael/quien_samael.htm|accessdate=25 December 2017|work=Samael.org}}</ref>\n*[[Riaz Ahmed Gohar Shahi]] of [[Kalki Avatar Foundation]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Pseudo-messianic movements in contemporary Muslim South Asia|first=Yoginder|last=Sikand|publisher=Global Media Publications|year=2008|page=100}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{refbegin|3}}\n* [[Second Coming]]\n* [[Dashavatara]]\n* [[End time]]\n* [[Kali (demon)|Kali]]\n* [[Koka and Vikoka]]\n* [[Lord of Light]]\n* [[Mahabharata]]\n* [[Maitreya]]\n* [[Paraclete]]\n* [[Ramayana]]\n* [[Suchandra]]\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|40em}}\n*{{cite book|last= Bryant |first=Edwin Francis | title=Krishna: A Sourcebook| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0z02cZe8PU8C|year= 2007| publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-803400-1}}\n* {{cite book | last = Dimmitt | first = Cornelia | first2 = J. A. B.  |last2 = van Buitenen | title = Classical Hindu Mythology: A Reader in the Sanskrit Puranas | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=re7CR2jKn3QC| publisher = Temple University Press (1st Edition: 1977) | year = 2012 | isbn =978-1-4399-0464-0  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first = Rosen|last= Dalal|year= 2014|title= Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide| publisher= Penguin|isbn= 978-8184752779| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC | ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Flood |first=Gavin |authorlink= |title=An Introduction to Hinduism |url=https://archive.org/details/introductiontohi0000floo |url-access=registration |year=1996 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |isbn= 0-521-43878-0}}\n*{{cite book|author=Ariel Glucklich|title=The Strides of Vishnu: Hindu Culture in Historical Perspective: Hindu Culture in Historical Perspective|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KtLScrjrWiAC| year=2008| publisher=Oxford University Press| isbn=978-0-19-971825-2 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Johnson |first = W.J. |title = A Dictionary of Hinduism | publisher = Oxford University Press | year = 2009 | isbn = 978-0-19-861025-0 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Rao | first = Velcheru Narayana | title = Purana Perennis: Reciprocity and Transformation in Hindu and Jaina Texts | chapter = Purana as Brahminic Ideology | isbn = 0-7914-1381-0 | editor = Doniger Wendy | year = 1993 | publisher = State University of New York Press | location = Albany  }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Ludo |last=Rocher| year= 1986| authorlink= Ludo Rocher| title= The Puranas| publisher= Otto Harrassowitz Verlag| isbn= 978-3447025225|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons+cat|Kalki|Kalki}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n\t\n{{VishnuAvatars}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Forms of Vishnu]]\n[[Category:Hindu eschatology]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophical concepts]]\n[[Category:Messianism]]\n[[Category:Akilattirattu Ammanai]]\n[[Category:Ayyavazhi mythology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|tenth incarnation of Vishnu in Hinduism}}\n{{other uses|Kalki (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox deity<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Hindu mythology-->\n| type        = Hindu\n| name        = Kalki\n| image       =Kalki Avatar by Ravi Varma.jpg\n| caption     = Kalki Avatar by [[Raja Ravi Varma]]\n| deity_of    = The tenth avatar of Vishnu\n| Devanagari  = \u0915\u0932\u094d\u0915\u093f  \t\n| Sanskrit_transliteration = Kalki\t \t\n| texts        = Hinduism: ''[[Mahabharat]]''<br/>''[[Puranas]]''<br>Buddhism: ''[[Kalachakra]]-Tantra''\n| mount       = Devadatta (i.e. [[White horse (mythology)#Hindu|White horse]])<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\"/><ref name=\"Dalal2010p188\">{{harvnb|Dalal|2014|p=188}}</ref> \t\n}}\n'''Kalki''', also called '''Kalkin''' or '''Karki''',<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\">{{cite book|author=J. L. Brockington|title=The Sanskrit Epics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HR-_LK5kl18C&pg=PA287 |year=1998|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-10260-4|pages=287\u2013288 with footnotes 126\u2013127}}</ref> is the tenth [[avatar]] of Hindu god [[Vishnu]] to end the [[Kali Yuga]], one of the four periods in the endless cycle of existence (''krita'') in [[Vaishnavism]] cosmology. He is described in the Puranas as the avatar who rejuvenates existence by ending the darkest and destructive period to remove [[adharma]] and ushering in the [[Satya Yuga]], while riding a white horse with a fiery sword.<ref name=\"Dalal2010p188\"/> The description and details of Kalki are inconsistent among the Puranic texts. He is, for example, only an invisible force destroying evil and chaos in some texts {{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}, while an actual person who kills those who persecute others, and portrayed as someone leading an army of dharmic warriors in some. \n\nKalki is also found in Buddhist texts. In [[Tibetan Buddhism]], the ''[[Kalachakra]]-Tantra'<ref name=\"Lopez2015p202\"/><ref name=\"Perry2017p220\"/><ref name=\"Dahla2006p90\"/>\n\nThe prophecy of Kalki avatar is believed by the followers of [[Vaishnavism]] sect of hinduism, as a part of the ten avatars of [[Vishnu]], who is cheif deity in vaishnavism. The [[Shaivism]] and [[Shaktism]] sects of hinduism may or may not believe in this prophecy, because Vishnu is not the cheif deity in those sects. \n\n\n\nAfter Kalki new yug known as Satyug will start.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name Kalki is derived based ''Kal'', which means \"time\" ([[kali yuga]]).<ref name=\"Klostermaier2006p75\">{{cite book|author=Klaus K. Klostermaier|title=Mythologies and Philosophies of Salvation in the Theistic Traditions of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CFQ9DgAAQBAJ |year=2006|publisher=Wilfrid Laurier Univ. Press|isbn=978-0-88920-743-1|page=75}}</ref> The literal meaning of Kalki is \"dirty, sinful\", which Brockington states does not make sense in the avatara context.<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\"/> This has led scholars such as Otto Schrader to suggest that the original term may have been ''karki'' (white, from the horse) which morphed into Kalki. This proposal is supported by two versions of ''Mahabharata'' manuscripts (e.g. the G3.6 manuscript) that have been found, where the Sanskrit verses name the avatar to be \"karki\", rather than \"kalki\".<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\" />\n\n==Description==\n{{Vaishnavism}}\nKalki is an avatara of Vishnu. Avatara means \"descent\" and refers to a descent of the divine into the material realm of human existence. The [[Garuda Purana]] lists [[Dasavatara of Vishnu#List|ten avatars]], with Kalki being the tenth.<ref>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|url=https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada|last=Gopal|first=Madan|year= 1990| page= [https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada/page/73 73]|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref> He is described as the avatar who appears at the end of the Kali Yuga. He ends the darkest, degenerating and chaotic stage of the Kali ''Yuga'' (period) to remove [[adharma]] and ushers in the [[Satya Yuga]], while riding a white horse with a fiery sword.<ref name=\"Dalal2010p188\"/><ref name=\"Doniger1999p629\">{{cite book| author1=Wendy Doniger|author2=Merriam-Webster, Inc|title=Merriam-Webster's Encyclopedia of World Religions| url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780877790440 | url-access=registration|year=1999|publisher=Merriam-Webster|isbn=978-0-87779-044-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780877790440/page/659 659]}}</ref> He restarts a new cycle of time.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ludo Rocher|editor=Ralph M. Rosen|title=Time and Temporality in the Ancient World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=It9KMklf4R4C&pg=PA91|date=22 March 2004|publisher=UPenn Museum of Archaeology|isbn=978-1-931707-67-1|pages=91\u201393}}</ref> He is described as a warrior in the Puranas.<ref name=\"Dalal2010p188\"/><ref name=\"Doniger1999p629\"/>\n\n===Wheel of Time Tantra===\nIn the Buddhist text ''Kalachakra Tantra'', the righteous kings are called Kalki (Kalkin, lit. chieftain) living in Sambhala. There are many Kalki in this text, each fighting barbarism, persecution and chaos. The last Kalki is called \"Cakrin\" and is predicted to end the chaos and degeneration by assembling a large army to eradicate the \"forces of Evil\".<ref name=\"Lopez2015p202\"/><ref name=\"Perry2017p220\"/> A great war and Armageddon will destroy the barbaric forces, states the text.<ref name=\"Lopez2015p202\"/><ref name=\"Perry2017p220\"/><ref name=\"Dahla2006p90\">[a] {{cite book|author=Bj\u00f6rn Dahla|title=Exercising Power: The Role of Religions in Concord and Conflict|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i_rWAAAAMAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Donner Institute for Research in Religious and Cultural History|isbn=978-952-12-1811-8|pages=90\u201391}}, '''Quote:''' \"(...) the Shambala-bodhisattva-king [Cakravartin Kalkin] and his army will defeat and destroy the enemy army.\";<br>[b] {{cite book|author=David Burton|title=Buddhism: A Contemporary Philosophical Investigation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=phddDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT193 |year=2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-83859-7|page=193}}<br>[c] {{cite book|author=Johan Elverskog |editor=Anna Akasoy|display-editors=etal|title=Islam and Tibet: Interactions Along the Musk Routes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZfWXIfbynwYC&pg=PA293 |year=2011|publisher=Ashgate Publishing |isbn=978-0-7546-6956-2|pages=293\u2013310}}</ref> According to Donald Lopez \u2013 a professor of Buddhist Studies, Kalki is predicted to start the new cycle of perfect era where \"People will live long, happy lives and righteousness will reign supreme\".<ref name=\"Lopez2015p202\"/> The text is significant in establishing the chronology of the Kalki idea to be from post-7th century, probably the 9th or 10th century.<ref name=\"JIN2017p49\">{{cite book|author=Yijiu JIN|title=Islam|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q-PzDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA49|year=2017|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=978-90-474-2800-8|pages=49\u201352}}</ref> Lopez states that the Buddhist text likely borrowed it from Hindu mythology.<ref name=\"Lopez2015p202\">{{cite book|author=Donald S. Lopez Jr.|title=Buddhism in Practice |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zaC4CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA202 |year=2015|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-8007-2|pages=202\u2013204}}</ref><ref name=\"Perry2017p220\">{{cite book|author=Perry Schmidt-Leukel|title=Religious Pluralism and Interreligious Theology: The Gifford Lectures |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ir3zDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT221 |year=2017|publisher=Orbis|isbn=978-1-60833-695-1|pages=220\u2013222}}</ref> Other scholars, such as Yijiu Jin, state that the text originated in Central Asia in the 10th-century, and Tibetan literature picked up a version of it in India around 1027 CE.<ref name=\"JIN2017p49\"/>\n\n==Development  ==\nThere is no mention of Kalki in the [[Vedas|Vedic]] literature.<ref name=academy81>{{cite book|title=Tattvad\u012bpa\u1e25: Journal of Academy of Sanskrit Research, Volume 5|page=81|publisher=The Academy|year=2001|quote=Kalki, as an incarnation of Visnu, is not found in the Vedic literature. But some of the features of that concept, viz., the fearful elements, the epithet Kalmallkinam (brilliant, remover of darkness) of Rudra, prompt us to admit him as the forerunner of Kalki.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Rabiprasad Mishra|title=Theory of Incarnation: Its Origin and Development in the Light of Vedic and Pur\u0101\u1e47ic References|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3XvXAAAAMAAJ |year=2000|publisher=Pratibha |isbn=978-81-7702-021-2|page=146}}, Quote: \"Kalki as an incarnation of Visnu is not mentioned in the Vedic literature.\"</ref> The epithet \"Kalmallkinam\", meaning \"brilliant remover of darkness\", is found in the Vedic literature for [[Rudra]] (later Shiva), which has been interpreted to be \"forerunner of Kalki\".<ref name=academy81/>\n\nKalki appears for the first time in the great war epic ''Mahabharata''.<ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2011p104\">{{cite book|author=Alf Hiltebeitel|title=Reading the Fifth Veda: Studies on the Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata - Essays by Alf Hiltebeitel|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=lLfHSOWKB-sC&pg=PA531|year=2011|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=978-90-04-18566-1|pages=89\u2013110, 530\u2013531}}</ref> The mention of Kalki in the ''Mahabharata'' occurs only once, over the verses 3.188.85\u20133.189.6.<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\"/> The Kalki avatar is found in the Maha-Puranas such as ''[[Vishnu Purana]]'',<ref>{{cite book |last=Wilson |first=Horace |authorlink=Horace Hayman Wilson |title=Vishnu Purana |year=2001 |publisher=Ganesha Publishing |isbn=1-86210-016-0 |page=72}}</ref> ''[[Matsya Purana]]'', and ''[[Bhagavata Purana]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Theory of Avat\u0101ra and Divinity of Chaitanya|first=Janmajit|last=Roy|page=39 |publisher = Atlantic Publishers}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Myths and Gods of India: The Classic Work on Hindu Polytheism from the Princeton Bollingen Series|first=Alain|last=Dani\u00e9lou|page=181|publisher=Inner Traditions / Bear & Co}}</ref> However, the details relating the Kalki mythologies are divergent between the Epic and the Puranas, as well as within the Puranas.<ref name=\"Mitchiner2000p68\">{{cite book|author=John E. Mitchiner|title=Traditions Of The Seven Rsis|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=phGzVwTTp_gC|year= 2000|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass |isbn= 978-81-208-1324-3|pages= 68\u201369 with footnotes}}</ref><ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2011p104\"/>\n\nIn the ''Mahabharata'', according to Hiltebeitel, Kalki is an extension of the [[Parasurama]] avatar legend warrior destroys those kings who were abusing their power to spread chaos, evil and persecution of the powerless. The Epic character of Kalki restores dharma, restores justice in the world, but does not end the cycle of existence.<ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2011p104\"/><ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2011p288\">{{cite book|author=Alf Hiltebeitel|title=Dharma: Its Early History in Law, Religion, and Narrative|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U4NF8pYxdvIC |year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-539423-8|pages=288\u2013292}}</ref> The Kalkin section in the ''Mahabharata'' occurs in the Markandeya section. There, states Luis Reimann, can \"hardly be any doubt that the Markandeya section is a late addition to the Epic. Making Yudhisthira ask a question about conditions at the end of Kali and the beginning of Krta \u2014 something far removed from his own situation \u2014 is merely a device for justifying the inclusion of this subject matter in the Epic.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Luis Gonz\u00e1lez Reimann|title=The Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata and the Yugas: India's Great Epic Poem and the Hindu System of World Ages|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=nXrXAAAAMAAJ|year =2002|publisher= Peter Lang|isbn= 978-0-8204-5530-3|pages= 89\u201399, quote is on page 97}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Cornelia Dimmitt, the \"clear and tidy\" systematization of Kalki and the remaining nine avatars of Vishnu is not found in any of the Maha-Puranas.<ref name=\"Dimmitt2012p63\"/> The coverage of Kalki in these Hindu texts is scant, in contrast to the legends of Matsya, Kurma, Varaha, Vamana, Narasimha and Krishna, all of which are repeatedly and extensively described. According to Dimmitt, this was likely because just like the concept of the Buddha as a Vishnu avatar, the concept of Kalki was \"somewhat in flux\" when the major Puranas were being compiled.<ref name=\"Dimmitt2012p63\"/><ref name=\"Dimmitt2012p63\">{{harvnb|Dimmitt|van Buitenen|2012|pp=63\u201364}}</ref>\n\nThis myth may have developed in the Hindu texts both as a reaction to the invasions of the Indian subcontinent by various armies over the centuries from its northwest, and the mythologies these invaders brought with them.<ref name=\"Brockington1998p287\"/><ref name=\"Doniger2004p235\">{{cite book|author=Wendy Doniger|title=Hindu Myths: A Sourcebook Translated from the Sanskrit|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQ4IMQAACAAJ |year=2004 |publisher =Penguin Books |isbn=978-0-14-044990-7|pages=235\u2013237}}</ref>\n\nAccording to John Mitchiner, the Kalki concept was likely borrowed \"in some measure from similar Jewish, Christian, Zoroastrian and other religions\".<ref name=\"Mitchiner2000p75\">{{cite book|author=John E. Mitchiner|title=Traditions Of The Seven Rsis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=phGzVwTTp_gC |year=2000|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1324-3|pages=75\u201376}}</ref> Mitchiner states that some Puranas such as the Yuga Purana do not mention Kalki and offer a different cosmology than the other Puranas. The Yuga Purana mythologizes in greater details the post-Maurya era Indo-Greek and Saka era, while the Manvantara theme containing the Kalki idea is mythologized greater in other Puranas.<ref name=\"Mitchiner2000p69\">{{cite book|author=John E. Mitchiner|title=Traditions Of The Seven Rsis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=phGzVwTTp_gC |year=2000|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1324-3|pages=69\u201376}}</ref><ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2011p104\" /> Luis Gonzales-Reimann concurs with Mitchiner, stating that the Yuga Purana does not mention Kalki.<ref name=\"Reimann2002p95\">{{cite book|author=Luis Gonz\u00e1lez-Reimann|title=The Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata and the Yugas: India's Great Epic Poem and the Hindu System of World Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nXrXAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-0-8204-5530-3|pages=95\u201399 }}</ref> In other texts such as the sections 2.36 and 2.37 of the Vayu Purana, states Reimann, it is not Kalkin who ends the Kali Yuga, but a different character named Pramiti.<ref name=\"Reimann2002p112\">{{cite book|author=Luis Gonz\u00e1lez Reimann|title=The Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata and the Yugas: India's Great Epic Poem and the Hindu System of World Ages|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=nXrXAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-0-8204-5530-3|pages=112\u2013113 note 39}}; Note: Reimann mentions some attempts to \"identify both Pramiti and Kalkin with historical rulers\".</ref> Most historians, states Arvind Sharma, link the development of Kalki mythology in Hinduism to the suffering caused by foreign invasions.<ref name=\"Sharma2012p244\">{{cite book|author=Arvind Sharma|title=Religious Studies and Comparative Methodology: The Case for Reciprocal Illumination|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CfZ9y5-FGPgC |year=2012|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-8325-1|pages=244\u2013245}}</ref>\n\n===Kalki Purana===\nA minor text named [[Kalki Purana]] is a relatively recent text, likely composed in [[Bengal]]. Its dating [[floruit]] is the 18th-century.{{sfn|Rocher|1986|p=183 with footnotes}} Wendy Doniger dates the Kalki mythology containing ''Kalki Purana'' to between 1500 and 1700 CE.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wendy Doniger|title=Textual Sources for the Study of Hinduism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KtZRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA5 |year=1988|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0-7190-1867-1|page=5}}</ref>\n\nIn the ''Kalki Purana'', Kalki marries princess Padmavati, the daughter of Brhadratha of Simhala.{{sfn|Rocher|1986|p=183 with footnotes}} He fights an evil army and many wars, ends evil but does not end existence. Kalki returns to Sambhala, inaugurates a new ''[[yuga]]'' for the good and then goes to heaven.{{sfn|Rocher|1986|p=183 with footnotes}}\n\n==Kalki Avatar in Sikhism==\n\n[[File:Kalki Avatar.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Kalki Avatar Punjab Hills, Guler, c. 1765.]]\n\nThe Kalki avatar appears in the historic [[Sikh]] texts, most notably in [[Dasam Granth]] as Nihakalanki, a text that is traditionally attributed to [[Guru Gobind Singh]].<ref name=\"Rinehart2011p29\">{{cite book|author=Robin Rinehart|title=Debating the Dasam Granth|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=58AVDAAAQBAJ |year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-975506-6|pages=29\u201330}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=W. H. McLeod|title=Sikhs of the Khalsa: A History of the Khalsa Rahit|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HIrXAAAAMAAJ |year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-565916-0|pages=149\u2013150}}</ref> The ''Chaubis Avatar'' (24 avatars) section mentions sage Matsyanra describing the appearance of Vishnu avatars to fight evil, greed, violence and ignorance. It includes Kalki as the twenty-fourth incarnation to lead the war between the forces of righteousness and unrighteousness, states Dhavan.<ref>{{cite book|author=Purnima Dhavan|title=When Sparrows Became Hawks: The Making of the Sikh Warrior Tradition, 1699-1799|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-7HJ5idB8_QC |year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-975655-1|pages=1 55\u2013157, 186 note 32}}</ref>\n\n==Features and iconography==\n[[File:Kalki_avatar_idol_in_rani_ki_vav_patan.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Statue Of god Kalki Avatar on wall of [[Rani ki vav|Rani Ki Vav]] (The Queens Stepwell) at Patan [[Gujarat]], [[India]]]]\n[Lord [[Shiva]] said to Lord Kalki:] \"This '''horse''' was manifested from [[Garuda]], and it can go anywhere at will and assume many different forms. Here also is a '''parrot''' [ [[Shuka]] ] that knows everything - past, present, and future. I would like to offer You both the horse and the parrot and so please accept them. By the influence of this horse and parrot, the people of the world will know You as a learned scholar of all scriptures who is a master of the art of releasing arrows, and thus the conqueror of all. I would also like to present You this sharp, strong '''sword''' and so please accept it. The handle of this sword is bedecked with jewels, and it is extremely powerful. As such, the sword will help You to reduce the heavy burden of the earth.\"<ref>Bhumipati Das. ''Sri Kalki Purana''. 2nd ed. India: Jai Nitai Press, 2011. pp. 33\u201334 (ch 3, text 25\u201327).</ref>\n\nThereafter, Lord Kalki picked up His brightly shining '''trident''' and '''bow and arrows''' and set out from His palace, riding upon His victorious horse and wearing His '''amulet'''.<ref>Bhumipati Das. ''Sri Kalki Purana''. 2nd ed. India: Jai Nitai Press, 2011. p. 36 (ch 3, text 36).</ref>\n\n[Shuka said to Padmavati:] [Lord Kalki] received a sword, horse, parrot, and '''shield''' from [[Shiva|Mahadeva]], as a benediction.<ref>Bhumipati Das. ''Sri Kalki Purana''. 2nd ed. India: Jai Nitai Press, 2011. p. 84 (ch 8, text 24).</ref>\n\n==Predictions about birth and arrival==\n\nIn the cyclic concept of time (''Puranic Kalpa''), [[Kaliyuga]] is variously estimated to last between 400,000 and 432,000 years. In some Vaishnava texts, Kalki is forecasted to appear on a white horse, at the end of Kaliyuga, to end the age of degeneration and to restore virtue and world order.<ref name=\"coulter2013\"/><ref name=\"Oxford University Press\">{{cite book|title=The Oxford Handbook of New Religious Movements, Volume 2|author1=James R. Lewis|author2=Inga B. Tollefsen|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=488}}</ref>\n\nKalki is described differently in Indian and non-Indian Buddhist manuscripts. The Indian texts state that Kalki will be born to Awejsirdenee and Bishenjun,<ref name=coulter2013/> or alternatively in the family of Sumati and Vishnuyasha.<ref name=\"emperor\"/>{{sfn|Rocher|1986|p=183}} He appears at the end of Kali Yuga to restore the order of the world.<ref name=coulter2013>{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Ancient Deities|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VWxekbhM1yEC|author1=Charles Russell Coulter|author2=Patricia Turner|publisher=Routledge|year=2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Oxford University Press\"/> Vishnuyasha is stated to be a prominent headman of the village called [[Shambhala]]. He will become the king, a \"Turner of the Wheel\", and one who triumphs. He will eliminate all barbarians and robbers, end ''adharma'', restart ''dharma'', and save the good people.<ref name=\"incarnation\">{{cite book|title=The Mahabharata, Volume 2: Book 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GfhJCgAAQBAJ|page=597\u2013598|year=1987|publisher=University of Chicago Press|author=J.A.B. van Buitenen}}</ref> After that, humanity will be transformed and will prevail on earth, and the golden age will begin.<ref name=\"incarnation\"/>\n\nIn the Kanchipuram temple, two relief Puranic panels depict Kalki, one relating to lunar (daughter-based) dynasty as mother of Kalki and another to solar (son-based) dynasty as father of Kalki.<ref name=\"emperor\"/> In these panels, states D Dennis Hudson, the story depicted is in terms of Kalki fighting and defeating asura [[Kali (demon)|Kali]]. He rides a white horse called Devadatta, ends evil, purifies everyone's minds and consciousness, and heralds the start of Krita Yuga.<ref name=\"emperor\">{{cite book|title=The Body of God: An Emperor's Palace for Krishna in Eighth-Century Kanchipuram|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2008|author=D Dennis Hudson|pages=333\u2013340}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dasavatar, 19th century.jpg|thumb|center|650px|19th-century [[Dashavatara]] painting (from left): Matsya, Kurma, Varaha, Narasimha, Vamana, Parashurama, Rama, Krishna, Buddha and Kalki.]]\n\n==People who claimed to be Kalki==\nList of people who have claimed to be the Kalki avatar:\n*[[Mirza Ghulam Ahmad]], founder of [[Ahmadiyya]] movement, claimed to be the Kalki Avatar, as well as [[Mahdi]].<ref>{{cite book | title = Oxford Handbook of Global Religions | first = Mark | last = Juergensmeyer | publisher =Oxford University Press | location = Oxford | year = 2006 | page = 520 | id = , ISBN (Ten digit): 0195137981| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lQMurMhRtfIC&pg=PA520| isbn = 978-0-19-513798-9 }}</ref>\n*In the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]], [[Bah\u00e1'u'll\u00e1h]] is identified as Kalki as well as the prophesied redeeming God at the end of the world, as claimed in Babism, Islam (Mahdi), Christianity (Messiah) and Buddhism (Maitreya).<ref name=\"Bassuk1987p146\">{{cite book|author=Daniel E Bassuk|title=Incarnation in Hinduism and Christianity: The Myth of the God-Man|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k3iwCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA146 |year=1987|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-1-349-08642-9|pages=146\u2013147}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=John M. Robertson|title=Tough Guys and True Believers: Managing Authoritarian Men in the Psychotherapy Room |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fTiZY_5wlJ4C&pg=PA62 |year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-81774-8|pages=62\u201363}}</ref>\n* Various [[Shia Muslim]] missionaries in South Asia \u2013 such as Siddiq Hussain \u2013 seeking to convert Hindus to their sect of Islam; they either claimed themselves to be Kalki, or claimed that \"all\" the [[The Twelve Imams|Shia Imams]] were Kalki, or claimed [[Muhammad]] was Kalki.<ref>{{cite book | last=Robinson | first=R. | last2=Clarke | first2=S. | title=Religious Conversion in India: Modes, Motivations, and Meanings | publisher=Oxford University Press | year=2003 | isbn=978-0-19-566329-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eNsoAAAAYAAJ | pages=44,108\u2013113}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Sikand | first=Y. | title=Muslims in India Since 1947: Islamic Perspectives on Inter-Faith Relations | publisher=Taylor & Francis | year=2004 | isbn=978-1-134-37825-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yf5aJi2loLcC  | pages=162\u2013171}}</ref>\n*[[Sri Bhagavan]], of Golden Age Foundation, Bhagavad Dharma, Kalki Dharma and the [[Oneness organisation|Oneness Organisation]], born on 7 March 1949.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KisRDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT488 The Oxford Handbook of New Religious Movements, Volume 2], p.488, James R. Lewis, Inga B. Tollefsen, Oxford University Press</ref>\n*[[Samael Aun Weor]], founder of the Universal Christian Gnostic Movement.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who is Samael Aun Weor?|url=http://www.samael.org/idiomas/ingles/paginas/1_quien_samael/quien_samael.htm|accessdate=25 December 2017|work=Samael.org}}</ref>\n*[[Riaz Ahmed Gohar Shahi]] of [[Kalki Avatar Foundation]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Pseudo-messianic movements in contemporary Muslim South Asia|first=Yoginder|last=Sikand|publisher=Global Media Publications|year=2008|page=100}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{refbegin|3}}\n* [[Second Coming]]\n* [[Dashavatara]]\n* [[End time]]\n* [[Kali (demon)|Kali]]\n* [[Koka and Vikoka]]\n* [[Lord of Light]]\n* [[Mahabharata]]\n* [[Maitreya]]\n* [[Paraclete]]\n* [[Ramayana]]\n* [[Suchandra]]\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|40em}}\n*{{cite book|last= Bryant |first=Edwin Francis | title=Krishna: A Sourcebook| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0z02cZe8PU8C|year= 2007| publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-803400-1}}\n* {{cite book | last = Dimmitt | first = Cornelia | first2 = J. A. B.  |last2 = van Buitenen | title = Classical Hindu Mythology: A Reader in the Sanskrit Puranas | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=re7CR2jKn3QC| publisher = Temple University Press (1st Edition: 1977) | year = 2012 | isbn =978-1-4399-0464-0  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first = Rosen|last= Dalal|year= 2014|title= Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide| publisher= Penguin|isbn= 978-8184752779| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC | ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Flood |first=Gavin |authorlink= |title=An Introduction to Hinduism |url=https://archive.org/details/introductiontohi0000floo |url-access=registration |year=1996 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |isbn= 0-521-43878-0}}\n*{{cite book|author=Ariel Glucklich|title=The Strides of Vishnu: Hindu Culture in Historical Perspective: Hindu Culture in Historical Perspective|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KtLScrjrWiAC| year=2008| publisher=Oxford University Press| isbn=978-0-19-971825-2 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Johnson |first = W.J. |title = A Dictionary of Hinduism | publisher = Oxford University Press | year = 2009 | isbn = 978-0-19-861025-0 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Rao | first = Velcheru Narayana | title = Purana Perennis: Reciprocity and Transformation in Hindu and Jaina Texts | chapter = Purana as Brahminic Ideology | isbn = 0-7914-1381-0 | editor = Doniger Wendy | year = 1993 | publisher = State University of New York Press | location = Albany  }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Ludo |last=Rocher| year= 1986| authorlink= Ludo Rocher| title= The Puranas| publisher= Otto Harrassowitz Verlag| isbn= 978-3447025225|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons+cat|Kalki|Kalki}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n\t\n{{VishnuAvatars}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Forms of Vishnu]]\n[[Category:Hindu eschatology]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophical concepts]]\n[[Category:Messianism]]\n[[Category:Akilattirattu Ammanai]]\n[[Category:Ayyavazhi mythology]]\n", "name_user": "124.253.6.116", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Sumit)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalki"}
{"title_page": "Meeta Pandit", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Meeta Pandit\n| image            = Meeta Pandit.jpg\n| caption          = In a concert\n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_place      = New Delhi, India\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = India\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]]\n| genre            = [[Indian classical music|Indian classical]], [[Hindustani classical music|Hindustani Classical Music]]\n| occupation       = [[Vocal]]ist\n| years_active     = 1983\u2013present\n| label            = [[EMI]], [[Saregama|SaReGaMa]], [[Underscore Records Pvt. Ltd.|Underscore]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = [http://www.meetapandit.com/  www.meetapandit.com]\n}}\n'''Meeta Pandit''' is a [[Hindustani classical music|Hindustani Classical]] [[vocal]]ist and a leading exponent of the [[Gwalior Gharana]]. She is the granddaughter and disciple of [[Krishnarao Shankar Pandit]] and daughter of Laxman Krishnarao Pandit. She is the sixth in the unbroken lineage and the first woman in the family to have taken up music as a profession.\n\n==Early life==\nMeeta was born in New Delhi, India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Meeta Pandit taking classical music to the young|url=http://zeenews.india.com/home/meeta-pandit-taking-classical-music-to-the-young_434740.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Zee Media Corporation Limited|publisher=Zee News|date=5 April 2008}}</ref> She is the daughter of Abha Pandit, a homemaker and Pt. Laxman Krishnarao Pandit, a veteran singer of the [[Gwalior gharana]] and [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] awardee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tagore Akademi Ratna and Tagore Akademi Puraskar |url=http://sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/tagoreawards.htm |website=Sangeet Natak Akademi |publisher=Sangeet Natak Akademi |accessdate=7 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140707094419/http://sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/tagoreawards.htm |archivedate=7 July 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lakshman Pandit is the last surviving doyen of the hoary Gwalior gharana|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/lakshman-pandit-the-last-surviving-doyen-of-the-hoary-gwalior-gharana/1/252809.html|website=India Today|publisher=India Today Group|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ongoing legacy|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/ongoing-legacy/article915171.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=27 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sangeet Natak Akademi Puraskar (Akademi Awards) |url=http://sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/awardeeslist.htm#HindustaniMusicVocal |website=Sangeet Natak Akademi |publisher=Sangeet Natak Akademi |accessdate=7 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530204253/http://sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/awardeeslist.htm |archivedate=30 May 2015 }}</ref> She spent her childhood in New Delhi, where she attended St. Mary\u2019s School until higher secondary, and earned a bachelor's degree in Commerce from [[Lady Sriram|Lady Sri Ram College]], [[Delhi University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Campus Days - Trading notes|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/dance/campus-days-trading-notes/article1156212.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=4 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lady Shri Ram College For Women|url=http://lsr.edu.in/Department-Profiles-2015.pdf|website=lsr.edu.in|publisher=Lady Shri Ram College|accessdate=7 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331075844/http://lsr.edu.in/Department-Profiles-2015.pdf|archive-date=31 March 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMeeta began training with her grandfather [[Padma Bhushan]] Pt. [[Krishnarao Shankar Pandit]] and her father Pt. L.K Pandit at the age of 3. Growing up in a house where music ustads and her father\u2019s disciples visited day in and day out, and all conversations centered around music, she was exposed to the finer aspects of music from a very young age.<ref>{{cite news|title=With music genres on tabs|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/375981/with-music-genres-tabs.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Deccan Herald|publisher=Deccan Herald|date=22 December 2013}}</ref> However, as a teenager, she was encouraged by her parents to take up a more stable profession than music, primarily due to the irregular working hours and solo travels involved, making it a difficult career choice for a woman.<ref>{{cite news|title=A young star of classical music traditions|url=http://www.sunday-guardian.com/artbeat/a-young-star-of-classical-music-traditions|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=The Sunday Guardian|date=26 October 2013}}</ref> Her elder brother Tushar Pandit was in fact, being groomed to take the family legacy forward. He was pursuing a Ph.D in [[Hindustani classical music]] when he met with a fatal road accident in [[New Delhi]] on September 1, 1994 at the age of 27.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obituary|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/TUSHAR-PANDIT/tributeshow/41411491.cms|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Bennette, Coleman & Co. Ltd.|publisher=The Times Of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=I Was Prepared For Everything God Had In Store For Me|url=http://www.tehelka.com/2014/06/i-was-prepared-for-everything-god-had-in-store-for-me/|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Tehelka.com|publisher=Tehelka.com|date=28 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093319/http://www.tehelka.com/2014/06/i-was-prepared-for-everything-god-had-in-store-for-me/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Upholding a family legacy, and also going beyond it|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/upholding-a-family-legacy-and-also-going-beyond-it/article1825467.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=9 April 2007}}</ref> Meeta, who was pursuing her bachelor's degree at the time and preparing for an [[MBA]], decided to take up the cudgels of carrying on the legacy and went on to pursue her masters in music. She completed her Ph.D in the [[Hindustani Classical music]] by the age of 27.\n\n==Career==\nMeeta gave her first performance on stage at the age of 9, during a 3-day music festival \u2018Prasang\u2019 organized by her grandfather, Pt. Krishnarao Shankar Pandit at [[Bharat Bhawan]], [[Bhopal]].<ref>{{cite news|title=A young star of classical music traditions|url=http://www.sunday-guardian.com/artbeat/a-young-star-of-classical-music-traditions|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=The Sunday Guardian|date=26 October 2013}}</ref> At the age of 15, she performed at the Sankat Mochan festival in [[Varanasi]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Meeta Pandit taking classical music to the young|url=http://zeenews.india.com/home/meeta-pandit-taking-classical-music-to-the-young_434740.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Zee Media Corporation Limited|publisher=Zee News|date=5 April 2008}}</ref> one of India\u2019s biggest annual classical music and dance festival.<ref>{{cite news|title=Let the music linger on|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/sankat-mochan-sangeet-samaroh-is-a-festival-of-openness/article7232003.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=21 May 2015}}</ref> She has performed at almost all the major classical music festivals of India and abroad which include the prestigious [[Sawai Gandharva Bhimsen Festival]] in 1999 and 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sawaigandharvabhimsenmahotsav.com/meeta-pandit|title=Meeta Pandit {{!}} sawai gandharva bhimsen mahotsav|work=sawaigandharvabhimsenmahotsav.com|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref> , the [[Dover Lane Music Conference]] , [[Kolkata]] in 2013 and 2019 and the [[Tansen Samaroh]] , [[Gwalior]] in 2011,2013 and 2019 . \n\nOther notable performances :\n\n*[[India International Centre]] (2011 & 2014)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iicdelhi.in/webcasts/view_webcast/a-celebration-of-carnatic-and-hindustani-music/|title=India International Centre{{!}}A Celebration of Carnatic and Hindustani Music|work=www.iicdelhi.in|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref>\n* Nadaneerajanam, as a part of [[Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams|Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanam]]\n*[[WOMADelaide]] , New Zealand and Australia\n*[[Melbourne Recital Centre]] (2015)\n*[[Darbar festival|Darbar Festival]] , Milton Court Concert Hall, London (2018) , [[United Kingdom]]\n* MERU Concert (2012, 2015) [[Netherlands]]\n* Ram Marathe Smruti Sangeet Samaroh , [[Thane]] (2017)\n* Pt. Jitendra Abhisheki Music Festival , [[Kala Academy]] ,Goa\n* Pancham Group, [[Satara (city)|Satara]]\n* Pracheen Kala Kendra, [[Chandigarh]] (2016)\n* Bagri Foundation, [[London]] (2015)\n* Ustad Alladiya Khan Sangeet Samaroh , [[Chembur]] , [[Mumbai]] (2015)\n* ViViDa Sangeet Sammelan , [[Pune]] (2013)\n*[[National Centre for the Performing Arts (India)|National Centre for the Performing Arts ,]]  [[Mumbai]]\n* Pt. Sharatchandra Arolkar Smruti Sangeet Samaroh organized by Khayal Trust , [[Mumbai]]\n*[[Harballabh Sangeet Sammelan]] , [[Jalandhar]] ,[[Punjab]] (1998 and 2015)\n* Shri Bhaini Sahib , Satguru Jagjit Singh Sangeet Sammelan (2017)\n* C.R. Vyas Sangeet Samaroh , Vadodara (2015)\n* Saptak Music Festival , Ahmedabad\n* Ustad Shaik Dawood Tabla Trust , Hyderabad\n* Soorya Festival ,Trivandrum ,Kerala\n* Krishna Gaan Sabha ,Chennai (2013 and 2015)\n* Delhi Classical Music Festival (2013)\n* Thumri Festival organized by Punjabi Academy ,Delhi (2017)\n* West Bengal State Music Academy Music Festival ,Kolkata (2017)\n* Jnana Pravaha Music Festival , Birla Sabhagar, organized by Sangeet Ashram , Kolkata (2011)\n* Strauss Reflected with David Murphy, [[John Suchet]] and Sinfonia Verdi at [[Cadogan Hall]] , London (2017)\n* Bharat Sanskriti Yatra , Stein Auditorium , [[India Habitat Centre]] , New Delhi\n* Madhya Pradesh Diwas , organized by the [[Government of Madhya Pradesh]] , Bhopal (2018)\n* 'Aadya' , [[Bharat Bhavan]] , Bhopal (2017)\n* ' Swara- Music for Life' ,organized by Banyan Tree Events ,Jaipur (2015)\n* De Meervaart , Netherlands\n*[[Jaipur Literature Festival|Zee Jaipur Literature Festival]] , Jaipur (2018)\n* SaMaPa Sangeet Sammelan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyexcelsior.com/city-of-temples-reverberates-with-vocal-recitals-of-srinivas-meeta/|title=City of Temples reverberates with vocal recitals of Srinivas, Meeta|last=Excelsior|first=Daily|date=2016-02-19|work=Jammu Kashmir Latest News {{!}} Tourism {{!}} Breaking News J&K|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref> , New Delhi and [[Jammu]] (2015)\n* 'Sapthak' , [[Bangalore]]\n*Akashwani Sangeet Sammelan\n*Shimla Classical Music Festival\n*Chowdhury House Music Conference, Kolkata (2019)\n*\n\n===1995\u20132000===\nBetween 1995 and 2005, Meeta performed extensively in prestigious festivals in India and abroad in France, Germany, [[London]], Switzerland, Norway, [[Rome]], United States, Russia and [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Meeta Pandit taking classical music to the young|url=http://zeenews.india.com/home/meeta-pandit-taking-classical-music-to-the-young_434740.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Zee Media Corporation Limited|publisher=Zee News|date=5 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nThrough a special project by French Embassy in [[New Delhi]], she stayed in [[Paris]] for three months as an \u201c[[Artist in Residence]]\u201d in 2003. There she collaborated with the [[Jazz pianist]], Allie Delfau, as a part of an Indo-French project.<ref>{{cite news|title=With music genres on tabs|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/375981/with-music-genres-tabs.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Deccan Herald|publisher=Deccan Herald|date=22 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe represented India as the Cultural Ambassador of India to Pakistan during the [[South Asian Association For Regional Co-Operation|South Asian Association for Regional Co-operation (SAARC)]] Summit in [[Islamabad]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|title=Upholding a family legacy, and also going beyond it|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/upholding-a-family-legacy-and-also-going-beyond-it/article1825467.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=9 April 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Music Maestro|url=http://www.womansera.com/showarticle2.php?id=1537|website=Womensera.com|publisher=Woman's Era|accessdate=7 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304095928/http://www.womansera.com/showarticle2.php?id=1537|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Public Service Broadcasting]] Trust and [[Prasar Bharati]] made a film titled \u2013 \u201cMeeta: Linking a Tradition with Today\u201d - which documents her life and growth as a singer in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=A young star of classical music traditions|url=http://www.sunday-guardian.com/artbeat/a-young-star-of-classical-music-traditions|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=The Sunday Guardian|date=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2005\u20132019===\nIn 2008, Meeta presented a music appreciation series called \u201cSwar Shringar\u201d on World Space Satellite Radio.<ref>{{cite news|title=With music genres on tabs|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/375981/with-music-genres-tabs.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Deccan Herald|publisher=Deccan Herald|date=22 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe collaborated with [[Amsterdam]] based [[Tabla|tabla player]], Heiko Dijker on an album called \u201cThe Luminance Project\u201d. This album was launched in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Indian classical needs support to sustain itself: Meeta Pandit|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/art-and-theatre/indian-classical-needs-support-to-sustain-itself-meeta-pandit_116598.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Zee Media Corporation Limited|publisher=Zee News|date=5 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince 2009, she has been a consultant with [[Indira Gandhi National Centre for the Arts]], [[New Delhi]], a premier government-funded arts organization in India. Among other things, she is involved in a project archiving more than 60 living [[maestros]] representing different [[genres]] and [[gharanas]] of [[Hindustani Classical music]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ongoing legacy|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/ongoing-legacy/article915171.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=27 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lady of Lineage|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/Lady-of-Lineage/2014/04/13/article2163298.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The New Indian Express Group|publisher=The Sunday Standard|date=13 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Diva of classical music|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110807/spectrum/book6.htm|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Tribune|publisher=Tribune India|date=7 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gems from classical music maestros recorded for posterity|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/gems-from-classical-music-maestros-recorded-for-posterity-114072300909_1.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Press Trust Of India|publisher=Business Standard|date=23 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nMeeta sings in different genres such as [[bhajan]], [[thumri]], [[tappa]] and [[ghazal]] and has proved her mastery over [[khayal]] and [[tappa]]. She actively promotes [[Indian Classical music]] worldwide. She has also been actively coaching budding singers from India and abroad in her attempt to spread [[Indian Classical Music]] globally.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music Maestro|url=http://www.womansera.com/showarticle2.php?id=1537|website=Womensera.com|publisher=Woman's Era|accessdate=7 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304095928/http://www.womansera.com/showarticle2.php?id=1537|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n\n==Awards==\n\n===Before 2005===\n* The 'Golden Voice of India' by the Singers Society of India - 1989\n* 'Sur Mani' by Sur Singar Samsad - 1992\n* 'Excellence in Music' Award: by Lady Shri Ram College - 1995\n* 'Full Circle Inner Flame Award', Full Circle Publishing Pvt. Ltd, 1999. (Awarded by [[Inder Kumar Gujral|I.K Gujral]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Meeta+Pandit/+wiki|website=last.fm|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n* 'Yuva Ratna' - Youth Excellence Award by Rotaract Club - 1999\n* 'Sur Mayank' - Pt. Nikhil Banerjee Smriti Award: Sangeet Bhavan (Lucknow) - 2001\n* 'Yuva Ojaswini Award' - 2005<ref>{{cite web|title=Meeta Pandit|url=http://sawaigandharvabhimsenmahotsav.com/meeta-pandit|website=Sawai Gandharva Bheemsen Mahotsav|publisher=Sawai Gandharva Bheemsen Mahotsav|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Meeta-pandit0150.jpg|alt=Meeta Pandit|thumb|320x320px]]\n\n===2006\u20132015===\n* FICCI Young Achiever Award for Indian classical music for 2007.\n* [[Bismillah Khan]] Award by [[Sangeet Natak Academy]] for 2007<ref>{{cite web|title=Ustad Bismillah Khan Yuva Puraskar 2007|url=http://sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/yuva2007.htm|website=sangeetnatak.gov.in|publisher=Sangeet Natak Akademi|accessdate=7 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404063238/http://www.sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/yuva2007.htm|archivedate=4 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Delhi Ratna - Art and Cultural Trust of India - 2009\n* Art Karat Award for her contribution to the field of music \u2013 2013\n* SaMaPa Yuva Ratna award for contribution to Classical Music \u2013 2015<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/santoor-maestro-bhajan-sopori-announces-samapa-awards/|title=Santoor maestro Bhajan Sopori announces SaMaPa awards|last=|first=|date=18 November 2015|work=|publisher=The Indian Express|agency=The Indian Express|via=|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n* Bhav Bhaveshwar Rashtriya Samman -2015\n* JP Award -2017 , instituted by the Loknayak Jaiprakash International Studies Centre , [[New Delhi]].\n\n==Discography==\n* Raga Rang ([[Saregama|SaReGaMa]])\n* Arpan ([[Underscore Records Pvt. Ltd.|Underscore Records]])\n* Young Maestros ([[Underscore Records Pvt. Ltd.|Underscore Records]] and [[Musictoday]]) \n* The Luminance Project ([[EMI]] Virgin)\n* Gharana Aur Parampara (Gwalior Gharana) - Vol 1 ([[Prasar Bharti]] and [[Doordarshan]])\n* Gharana Aur Parampara (Gwalior Gharana) - Vol 2 ([[Prasar Bharti]] and [[Doordarshan]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandit, Meeta}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian female classical singers]]\n[[Category:Women musicians from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Singers from Delhi]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Meeta Pandit\n| image            = Meeta Pandit.jpg\n| caption          = In a concert\n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_place      = New Delhi, India\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = India\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]]\n| genre            = [[Indian classical music|Indian classical]], [[Hindustani classical music|Hindustani Classical Music]]\n| occupation       = [[Vocal]]ist\n| years_active     = 1983\u2013present\n| label            = [[EMI]], [[Saregama|SaReGaMa]], [[Underscore Records Pvt. Ltd.|Underscore]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = [http://www.meetapandit.com/  www.meetapandit.com]\n}}\n'''Meeta Pandit''' is a [[Hindustani classical music|Hindustani Classical]] [[vocal]]ist belonging to the [[Gwalior Gharana]]. She is the granddaughter and disciple of [[Krishnarao Shankar Pandit]] and daughter of Laxman Krishnarao Pandit. She is the sixth in the unbroken lineage and the first woman in the family to have taken up music as a profession.\n\n==Early life==\nMeeta was born in New Delhi, India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Meeta Pandit taking classical music to the young|url=http://zeenews.india.com/home/meeta-pandit-taking-classical-music-to-the-young_434740.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Zee Media Corporation Limited|publisher=Zee News|date=5 April 2008}}</ref> She is the daughter of Abha Pandit, a homemaker and Pt. Laxman Krishnarao Pandit, an exponent of the [[Gwalior gharana]] and [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] awardee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tagore Akademi Ratna and Tagore Akademi Puraskar |url=http://sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/tagoreawards.htm |website=Sangeet Natak Akademi |publisher=Sangeet Natak Akademi |accessdate=7 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140707094419/http://sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/tagoreawards.htm |archivedate=7 July 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lakshman Pandit is the last surviving doyen of the hoary Gwalior gharana|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/lakshman-pandit-the-last-surviving-doyen-of-the-hoary-gwalior-gharana/1/252809.html|website=India Today|publisher=India Today Group|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ongoing legacy|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/ongoing-legacy/article915171.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=27 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sangeet Natak Akademi Puraskar (Akademi Awards) |url=http://sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/awardeeslist.htm#HindustaniMusicVocal |website=Sangeet Natak Akademi |publisher=Sangeet Natak Akademi |accessdate=7 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530204253/http://sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/awardeeslist.htm |archivedate=30 May 2015 }}</ref> She spent her childhood in New Delhi, where she attended St. Mary\u2019s School until higher secondary, and earned a bachelor's degree in Commerce from [[Lady Sriram|Lady Sri Ram College]], [[Delhi University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Campus Days - Trading notes|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/dance/campus-days-trading-notes/article1156212.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=4 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lady Shri Ram College For Women|url=http://lsr.edu.in/Department-Profiles-2015.pdf|website=lsr.edu.in|publisher=Lady Shri Ram College|accessdate=7 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331075844/http://lsr.edu.in/Department-Profiles-2015.pdf|archive-date=31 March 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMeeta began training with her grandfather [[Padma Bhushan]] Pt. [[Krishnarao Shankar Pandit]] and her father Pt. L.K Pandit at the age of 3. Growing up in a house where music ustads and her father\u2019s disciples visited day in and day out, and all conversations centered around music, she was exposed to the finer aspects of music from a very young age.<ref>{{cite news|title=With music genres on tabs|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/375981/with-music-genres-tabs.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Deccan Herald|publisher=Deccan Herald|date=22 December 2013}}</ref> However, as a teenager, she was encouraged by her parents to take up a more stable profession than music, primarily due to the irregular working hours and solo travels involved, making it a difficult career choice for a woman.<ref>{{cite news|title=A young star of classical music traditions|url=http://www.sunday-guardian.com/artbeat/a-young-star-of-classical-music-traditions|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=The Sunday Guardian|date=26 October 2013}}</ref> Her elder brother Tushar Pandit was in fact, being groomed to take the family legacy forward. He was pursuing a Ph.D in [[Hindustani classical music]] when he met with a fatal road accident in [[New Delhi]] on September 1, 1994 at the age of 27.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obituary|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/TUSHAR-PANDIT/tributeshow/41411491.cms|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Bennette, Coleman & Co. Ltd.|publisher=The Times Of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=I Was Prepared For Everything God Had In Store For Me|url=http://www.tehelka.com/2014/06/i-was-prepared-for-everything-god-had-in-store-for-me/|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Tehelka.com|publisher=Tehelka.com|date=28 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093319/http://www.tehelka.com/2014/06/i-was-prepared-for-everything-god-had-in-store-for-me/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Upholding a family legacy, and also going beyond it|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/upholding-a-family-legacy-and-also-going-beyond-it/article1825467.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=9 April 2007}}</ref> Meeta, who was pursuing her bachelor's degree at the time and preparing for an [[MBA]], decided to take up the cudgels of carrying on the legacy and went on to pursue her masters in music. She completed her Ph.D in the [[Hindustani Classical music]] by the age of 27.\n\n==Career==\nMeeta gave her first performance on stage at the age of 9, during a 3-day music festival \u2018Prasang\u2019 organized by her grandfather, Pt. Krishnarao Shankar Pandit at [[Bharat Bhawan]], [[Bhopal]].<ref>{{cite news|title=A young star of classical music traditions|url=http://www.sunday-guardian.com/artbeat/a-young-star-of-classical-music-traditions|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=The Sunday Guardian|date=26 October 2013}}</ref> At the age of 15, she performed at the Sankat Mochan festival in [[Varanasi]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Meeta Pandit taking classical music to the young|url=http://zeenews.india.com/home/meeta-pandit-taking-classical-music-to-the-young_434740.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Zee Media Corporation Limited|publisher=Zee News|date=5 April 2008}}</ref> one of India\u2019s biggest annual classical music and dance festival.<ref>{{cite news|title=Let the music linger on|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/sankat-mochan-sangeet-samaroh-is-a-festival-of-openness/article7232003.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=21 May 2015}}</ref> She has performed at almost all the major classical music festivals of India and abroad which include the prestigious [[Sawai Gandharva Bhimsen Festival]] in 1999 and 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sawaigandharvabhimsenmahotsav.com/meeta-pandit|title=Meeta Pandit {{!}} sawai gandharva bhimsen mahotsav|work=sawaigandharvabhimsenmahotsav.com|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref> , the [[Dover Lane Music Conference]] , [[Kolkata]] in 2013 and 2019 and the [[Tansen Samaroh]] , [[Gwalior]] in 2011,2013 and 2019 .\nOther notable performances :\n\n* [[India International Centre]] (2011 & 2014)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iicdelhi.in/webcasts/view_webcast/a-celebration-of-carnatic-and-hindustani-music/|title=India International Centre{{!}}A Celebration of Carnatic and Hindustani Music|work=www.iicdelhi.in|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref>\n* Nadaneerajanam, as a part of [[Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanams|Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanam]] \n* [[WOMADelaide]] , New Zealand and Australia\n* [[Melbourne Recital Centre]] (2015)\n* [[Darbar festival|Darbar Festival]] , Milton Court Concert Hall, London (2018) , [[United Kingdom]]\n* MERU Concert (2012, 2015) [[Netherlands]]\n* Ram Marathe Smruti Sangeet Samaroh , [[Thane]] (2017)\n* Pt. Jitendra Abhisheki Music Festival , [[Kala Academy]] ,Goa\n* Pancham Group , [[Satara (city)|Satara]] \n* Pracheen Kala Kendra , [[Chandigarh]] (2016)\n* Bagri Foundation, [[London]] (2015)\n* Ustad Alladiya Khan Sangeet Samaroh , [[Chembur]] , [[Mumbai]] (2015)\n* ViViDa Sangeet Sammelan , [[Pune]] (2013)\n* [[National Centre for the Performing Arts (India)|National Centre for the Performing Arts ,]]  [[Mumbai]]\n* Pt. Sharatchandra Arolkar Smruti Sangeet Samaroh organized by Khayal Trust , [[Mumbai]]\n* [[Harballabh Sangeet Sammelan]] , [[Jalandhar]] ,[[Punjab]] (1998 and 2015)\n* Shri Bhaini Sahib , Satguru Jagjit Singh Sangeet Sammelan (2017)\n* C.R. Vyas Sangeet Samaroh , Vadodara (2015)\n* Saptak Music Festival , Ahmedabad\n* Ustad Shaik Dawood Tabla Trust , Hyderabad\n* Soorya Festival ,Trivandrum ,Kerala\n* Krishna Gaan Sabha ,Chennai (2013 and 2015)\n* Delhi Classical Music Festival (2013)\n* Thumri Festival organized by Punjabi Academy ,Delhi (2017)\n* West Bengal State Music Academy Music Festival ,Kolkata (2017)\n* Jnana Pravaha Music Festival , Birla Sabhagar, organized by Sangeet Ashram , Kolkata (2011)\n* Strauss Reflected with David Murphy, [[John Suchet]] and Sinfonia Verdi at [[Cadogan Hall]] , London (2017)\n* Bharat Sanskriti Yatra , Stein Auditorium , [[India Habitat Centre]] , New Delhi\n* Madhya Pradesh Diwas , organized by the [[Government of Madhya Pradesh]] , Bhopal (2018)\n* 'Aadya' , [[Bharat Bhavan]] , Bhopal (2017)\n* ' Swara- Music for Life' ,organized by Banyan Tree Events ,Jaipur (2015)\n* De Meervaart , Netherlands\n* [[Jaipur Literature Festival|Zee Jaipur Literature Festival]] , Jaipur (2018) \n* SaMaPa Sangeet Sammelan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyexcelsior.com/city-of-temples-reverberates-with-vocal-recitals-of-srinivas-meeta/|title=City of Temples reverberates with vocal recitals of Srinivas, Meeta|last=Excelsior|first=Daily|date=2016-02-19|work=Jammu Kashmir Latest News {{!}} Tourism {{!}} Breaking News J&K|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref> , New Delhi and [[Jammu]] (2015)\n* 'Sapthak' , [[Bangalore]] \n\n===1995\u20132000===\nBetween 1995 and 2005, Meeta performed extensively in prestigious festivals in India and abroad in France, Germany, [[London]], Switzerland, Norway, [[Rome]], United States, Russia and [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Meeta Pandit taking classical music to the young|url=http://zeenews.india.com/home/meeta-pandit-taking-classical-music-to-the-young_434740.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Zee Media Corporation Limited|publisher=Zee News|date=5 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nThrough a special project by French Embassy in [[New Delhi]], she stayed in [[Paris]] for three months as an \u201c[[Artist in Residence]]\u201d in 2003. There she collaborated with the [[Jazz pianist]], Allie Delfau, as a part of an Indo-French project.<ref>{{cite news|title=With music genres on tabs|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/375981/with-music-genres-tabs.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Deccan Herald|publisher=Deccan Herald|date=22 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe represented India as the Cultural Ambassador of India to Pakistan during the [[South Asian Association For Regional Co-Operation|South Asian Association for Regional Co-operation (SAARC)]] Summit in [[Islamabad]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|title=Upholding a family legacy, and also going beyond it|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/upholding-a-family-legacy-and-also-going-beyond-it/article1825467.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=9 April 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Music Maestro|url=http://www.womansera.com/showarticle2.php?id=1537|website=Womensera.com|publisher=Woman's Era|accessdate=7 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304095928/http://www.womansera.com/showarticle2.php?id=1537|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Public Service Broadcasting]] Trust and [[Prasar Bharati]] made a film titled \u2013 \u201cMeeta: Linking a Tradition with Today\u201d - which documents her life and growth as a singer in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=A young star of classical music traditions|url=http://www.sunday-guardian.com/artbeat/a-young-star-of-classical-music-traditions|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=The Sunday Guardian|date=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2005\u20132019===\nIn 2008, Meeta presented a music appreciation series called \u201cSwar Shringar\u201d on World Space Satellite Radio.<ref>{{cite news|title=With music genres on tabs|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/375981/with-music-genres-tabs.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Deccan Herald|publisher=Deccan Herald|date=22 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe collaborated with [[Amsterdam]] based [[Tabla|tabla player]], Heiko Dijker on an album called \u201cThe Luminance Project\u201d. This album was launched in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Indian classical needs support to sustain itself: Meeta Pandit|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/art-and-theatre/indian-classical-needs-support-to-sustain-itself-meeta-pandit_116598.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Zee Media Corporation Limited|publisher=Zee News|date=5 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince 2009, she has been a consultant with [[Indira Gandhi National Centre for the Arts]], [[New Delhi]], a premier government-funded arts organization in India. Among other things, she is involved in a project archiving more than 60 living [[maestros]] representing different [[genres]] and [[gharanas]] of [[Hindustani Classical music]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ongoing legacy|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/ongoing-legacy/article915171.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Hindu|publisher=The Hindu|date=27 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lady of Lineage|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/Lady-of-Lineage/2014/04/13/article2163298.ece|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The New Indian Express Group|publisher=The Sunday Standard|date=13 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Diva of classical music|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110807/spectrum/book6.htm|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=The Tribune|publisher=Tribune India|date=7 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gems from classical music maestros recorded for posterity|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/gems-from-classical-music-maestros-recorded-for-posterity-114072300909_1.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|agency=Press Trust Of India|publisher=Business Standard|date=23 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nMeeta sings in different genres such as [[bhajan]], [[thumri]], [[tappa]] and [[ghazal]] and has proved her mastery over [[khayal]] and [[tappa]]. She actively promotes [[Indian Classical music]] worldwide. She has also been actively coaching budding singers from India and abroad in her attempt to spread [[Indian Classical Music]] globally.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music Maestro|url=http://www.womansera.com/showarticle2.php?id=1537|website=Womensera.com|publisher=Woman's Era|accessdate=7 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304095928/http://www.womansera.com/showarticle2.php?id=1537|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n\n==Awards==\n\n===Before 2005===\n* The 'Golden Voice of India' by the Singers Society of India - 1989\n* 'Sur Mani' by Sur Singar Samsad - 1992\n* 'Excellence in Music' Award: by Lady Shri Ram College - 1995\n* 'Full Circle Inner Flame Award', Full Circle Publishing Pvt. Ltd, 1999. (Awarded by [[Inder Kumar Gujral|I.K Gujral]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Meeta+Pandit/+wiki|website=last.fm|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n* 'Yuva Ratna' - Youth Excellence Award by Rotaract Club - 1999\n* 'Sur Mayank' - Pt. Nikhil Banerjee Smriti Award: Sangeet Bhavan (Lucknow) - 2001\n* 'Yuva Ojaswini Award' - 2005<ref>{{cite web|title=Meeta Pandit|url=http://sawaigandharvabhimsenmahotsav.com/meeta-pandit|website=Sawai Gandharva Bheemsen Mahotsav|publisher=Sawai Gandharva Bheemsen Mahotsav|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Meeta-pandit0150.jpg|alt=Meeta Pandit|thumb|320x320px]]\n\n===2006\u20132015===\n* FICCI Young Achiever Award for Indian classical music for 2007.\n* [[Bismillah Khan]] Award by [[Sangeet Natak Academy]] for 2007<ref>{{cite web|title=Ustad Bismillah Khan Yuva Puraskar 2007|url=http://sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/yuva2007.htm|website=sangeetnatak.gov.in|publisher=Sangeet Natak Akademi|accessdate=7 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404063238/http://www.sangeetnatak.gov.in/sna/yuva2007.htm|archivedate=4 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Delhi Ratna - Art and Cultural Trust of India - 2009\n* Art Karat Award for her contribution to the field of music \u2013 2013\n* SaMaPa Yuva Ratna award for contribution to Classical Music \u2013 2015<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/santoor-maestro-bhajan-sopori-announces-samapa-awards/|title=Santoor maestro Bhajan Sopori announces SaMaPa awards|last=|first=|date=18 November 2015|work=|publisher=The Indian Express|agency=The Indian Express|via=|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n* Bhav Bhaveshwar Rashtriya Samman -2015\n* JP Award -2017 , instituted by the Loknayak Jaiprakash International Studies Centre , [[New Delhi]].\n\n==Discography==\n* Raga Rang ([[Saregama|SaReGaMa]])\n* Arpan ([[Underscore Records Pvt. Ltd.|Underscore Records]])\n* Young Maestros ([[Underscore Records Pvt. Ltd.|Underscore Records]] and [[Musictoday]]) \n* The Luminance Project ([[EMI]] Virgin)\n* Gharana Aur Parampara (Gwalior Gharana) - Vol 1 ([[Prasar Bharti]] and [[Doordarshan]])\n* Gharana Aur Parampara (Gwalior Gharana) - Vol 2 ([[Prasar Bharti]] and [[Doordarshan]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandit, Meeta}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian female classical singers]]\n[[Category:Women musicians from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Singers from Delhi]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women singers]]\n", "name_user": "Compsci49", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meeta_Pandit"}
{"title_page": "Fetal hemoglobin", "text_new": "{{Infobox heteropolypeptide\n | heteropolymer = Fetal hemoglobin \n | polymer_type = 4 subunits, \u03b1<sub>2</sub>\u03b3<sub>2</sub>\n | protein_type = [[metalloprotein]], [[globulin]]\n | function = [[oxygen]]-transport\n | cofactors = [[heme]] (4)\n | image = Structure of Fetal Hemoglobin (HbF).png\n | image_source = Structure of Fetal Hemoglobin (HbF). The '''2\u03b1''' and '''2\u03b3''' subunits are in red and yellow, respectively, and the iron-containing [[heme]] groups in green. From {{PDB|4MQJ}}, by authors Soman, J. and Olson J.S.\n | SubunitCount = 4\n | subunit1 = Hb-\u03b11\n | gene1 = [[HBA1]]\n | locus1 = [[Chromosome 16|Chr. 16]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBA1#location?chromosome=16p13.3 p13.3]\n | subunit2 = Hb-\u03b12\n | gene2 = [[HBA2]]\n | locus2 = [[Chromosome 16|Chr. 16]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBA2#location?chromosome=16p13.3 p13.3]\n | subunit3 = Hb-\u03b31\n | gene3 = [[HBG1]]\n | locus3 = [[Chromosome 11|Chr. 11]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG1#location?chromosome=11p15.4 p15.4]\n | subunit4 = Hb-\u03b32\n | gene4 = [[HBG2]]\n | locus4 = [[Chromosome 11|Chr. 11]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG2#location?chromosome=11p15.4 p15.4]\n}}\n\n'''Fetal hemoglobin''', or '''foetal haemoglobin''' (also '''hemoglobin F''', '''HbF''', or '''\u03b1<sub>2</sub>\u03b3<sub>2</sub>''') is the main [[oxygen]] [[transport protein|carrier protein]] in the human [[fetus]]. Hemoglobin F is found in fetal red blood cells and it is involved in transporting oxygen from the mother's [[bloodstream]] to organs and tissues in the fetus. It is produced at around 6 weeks of pregnancy <ref name=\"David 1998\">{{cite book |last= Linch|first= David|date= 1998|title= Encyclopedia of Immunology (second edition)|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B0122267656001031 |publisher= Elsevier|isbn= 978-0-12-226765-9}}</ref> and the levels remain high after birth until the baby is roughly 2-4 months old.<ref name=\"Schechter2008\">{{Cite journal | author=Schechter A | title=Hemoglobin research and the origins of molecular medicine | journal=[[Blood]] | volume=112(10) | year=2008 | pages=3927\u20133938 | doi=10.1182/blood-2008-04-078188 }}</ref> Hemoglobin F has a different composition from the adult forms of [[hemoglobin]], which allows it to bind (or attach to) oxygen more strongly. This way, the developing fetus is able to retrieve oxygen from the mother's bloodstream, which occurs through the [[placenta]] found in the mother\u2019s [[uterus]].<ref name=\"Wang Y & Zhao S\">{{Cite book | authors= Wang Y, Zhao S| title= Vascular Biology of the Placenta| year=2010 | chapter=Chapter 2: Placental Blood Circulation | publisher=Morgan & Claypool Life Sciences }}</ref>\n\n\nIn the newborn, levels of hemoglobin F gradually decrease and reach adult levels (less than 1% of total hemoglobin) usually within 1 year of life, as adult forms of hemoglobin begin to be produced.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\">{{cite book |last= Wild|first= Barbara|date= 2017|title= Dacie and Lewis Practical Haematology (twelfth edition)|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B978070206696200014X |publisher= Elsevier|isbn= 978-0-7020-6696-2}}</ref> Diseases such as [[\u03b2-thalassemia]], which affect components of the adult hemoglobin, can delay this switch and cause hemoglobin F levels to be higher than normal in these patients.<ref name=\"Orapan2016\">{{Cite journal | author=Orapan S & Suthat F| title=Fetal hemoglobin regulation in \u03b2-thalassemia: heterogeneity, modifiers and therapeutic approaches | journal=[[Expert review of hematology]] | volume=9(12) |year=2016 | pages=1129\u20131137 | doi=10.1080/17474086.2016.1255142 }}</ref> In sickle cell anaemia, increasing the production of hemoglobin F has been used as a treatment, as it relieves some of the symptoms of the disease.<ref name=\"pmid18458272\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Lanzkron S, Strouse JJ, Wilson R, etal |title=Systematic review: Hydroxyurea for the treatment of adults with sickle cell disease |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |volume=148 |issue=12 |pages=939\u201355 |date=June 2008 |pmid=18458272 |doi= 10.7326/0003-4819-148-12-200806170-00221|url= |pmc=3256736}}</ref>\n\n\n==Structure and genetics==\nHemoglobin F, like hemoglobin forms found in adults ([[hemoglobin A]] and [[hemoglobin A2]]), have four [[protein subunit|subunits]] or chains. Each subunit contains a [[heme]] group with an iron element which is key in allowing the binding and unbinding of oxygen. As hemoglobin F has 4 heme groups, it can bind to up to four oxygen molecules.<ref name=brsphys>{{cite book |author=Costanzo, Linda S. |title=Physiology |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location=Hagerstwon, MD |year=2007 |isbn=978-0781773119 |url=https://archive.org/details/physiology00cost_0 }}</ref> It is composed of '''two \u03b1 (alpha)''' subunits and '''two \u03b3 (gamma)''' subunits, whereas hemoglobin A (97% of total hemoglobin in adults) is composed of two \u03b1 and two \u03b2 (beta) subunits.\n\nIn humans, the \u03b1 subunit is encoded on [[chromosome 16 (human)|chromosome 16]] and the \u03b3 subunit is encoded on [[chromosome 11 (human)|chromosome 11]]. There are 2 very similar [[gene]]s that code for the \u03b1 subunit, [[HBA1]] and [[HBA2]]. The protein that they produce is identical, but they differ in gene regulatory regions that determine when or how much of the protein is produced. This leads to HBA1 and HBA2 each contributing with 40% and 60%, respectively, of the total of \u03b1 subunits produced. As a consequence, mutations on the HBA2 gene are expected to have a stronger effect than mutations on the HBA1 gene.<ref name=\"Samaneh2018\">{{Cite journal | author=Samaneh F & Cornelis L| title=Molecular basis of \u03b1-thalassemia | journal=[[Blood cells, Molecules and Diseases]] | volume=70 |year=2018 | pages=43\u201353 | doi=10.1016/j.bcmd.2017.09.004 }}</ref> \nThere are also two similar copies of the gene coding for the \u03b3 subunit, HBG1 and HBG2, but the protein produced is slightly different, just in one [[amino acid|protein unit]]: HBG1 codes for the protein form with an [[alanine]] at position 136, whereas HBG2 codes for a [[glycine]] (see [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG1|NIH]).\n\n==When is hemoglobin F produced==\n[[File:Postnatal genetics en.svg|thumb|300px|[[Gene expression]] of hemoglobin before and after birth, also showing the cells types and organs where different subunits are being produced over time (data on ''Wood W.G.'', (1976). '''Br. Med. Bull. 32, 282.''') Figure last adapted by user Leonid 2.]]\n\nDuring the first 3 months of pregnancy, the main form of hemoglobin in the embryo/fetus is [[embryonic hemoglobin]], which has 3 variants depending on the types of subunits it contains. The production of hemoglobin F starts from week 6, but it's only from 3 months onwards that it becomes the main type found in fetal red blood cells.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\"/>\nThe switch to produce adult forms of hemoglobin (essentially Hemoglobin A) starts at around 40 weeks of gestation, which is close to the expected time of birth.<ref name=\"David 1998\"/> At birth, hemoglobin F accounts for 50-95% of the infant's hemoglobin and at around 6 months after birth, hemoglobin A becomes the predominant type. By the time the baby is one year old, the proportions of different types of hemoglobin are expected to approximate the adult levels, with hemoglobin F reduced to very low levels.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\" /> The small proportion of red blood cells containing hemoglobin F are called F-cells.\n\nIn healthy adults, the composition of hemoglobin is hemoglobin A (~97%), hemoglobin A2 (2.2 - 3.5%) and hemoglobin F (<1%).<ref name=\"Caroline 2012\">{{Cite journal | author=Caroline T & Andrew L| title= Physiology of haemoglobin| journal=[[Continuing Education in Anaesthesia Critical Care & Pain]] | volume=12(5) |year=2012 | pages=251\u2013256 | doi=10.1093/bjaceaccp/mks025 }}</ref>\n\nCertain genetic abnormalities can cause the switch to adult hemoglobin synthesis to fail, resulting in a condition known as [[hereditary persistence of fetal hemoglobin]] (HPFH).\n\n==Binding to oxygen==\n===Why hemoglobin F has higher oxygen affinity===\nThe 4 hemes, which are the oxygen-binding parts of hemoglobin, are similar between hemoglobin F and other types of hemoglobin, including hemoglobin A. Thus, the key feature that allows hemoglobin F to bind more strongly to oxygen is by having \u03b3 subunits (instead of \u03b2, for example). In fact, some naturally existing molecules in our body can bind to hemoglobin and change its binding affinity for oxygen. One of the molecules is [[2,3-bisphosphoglycerate|2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG)]] and it enhances hemoglobin\u2019s ability to release oxygen.<ref name=\"Gerald 2018\">  {{Cite book | authors= Litwack G| title= Human Biochemistry | year=2018 | chapter=Chapter 8 \u2013 Glycolysis and Glocuneogenesis | publisher=Academic press| isbn = 978-0-12-383864-3}} </ref> 2,3-BPG interacts much more with hemoglobin A than hemoglobin F. This is because the adult \u03b2 subunit has more positive charges than the fetal \u03b3 subunit, which attract the negative charges from 2,3-BPG. Due to the preference of 2,3-BPG for hemoglobin A, hemoglobin F binds to oxygen with more affinity, in average.<ref name=\"Duane 2016\"> {{cite web |url=https://biosci.mcdb.ucsb.edu/biochemistry/tw-hbn/hbf/hbf-overview.htm\n|title= Comparing the molecular structure differences between HbF and HbA that affect BPG binding|last= Sears|first= Duane|date= 2016|website= https://biosci.mcdb.ucsb.edu/|publisher= Biosci Portal |access-date= 11 March 2020}} </ref>\n\n===Quantification of oxygen binding=== \nTo quantify how strongly a certain type of hemoglobin binds to oxygen (or its affinity for oxygen), a parameter called P50 is often used. In a given situation, P50 can be understood as the minimum concentration of oxygen needed for 50% of the hemoglobin molecules to bind to it.<ref name=\"Vibhu2006\">  {{Cite book | authors= Awasthi V, Goins E and Phillips W| title= Blood Substitutes| year=2006 | chapter=Chapter 43 \u2013 Liposome-encapsulated hemoglobin: history, preparation and evaluation | publisher=Academic press| isbn = 978-0-12-759760-7}} </ref> For example, Hemoglobin F has a lower P50 than hemoglobin A. This means that if we have the same amount of hemoglobin F and hemoglobin A in the blood and add oxygen to it, half of hemoglobin F will bind to oxygen before half of hemoglobin A manages to do so. Therefore, a lower P50 means stronger binding or higher affinity for oxygen. \n\nFor reference, the P50 of fetal hemoglobin is roughly 19 mmHg (a measure of pressure), whereas adult hemoglobin is approximately 26.8 mmHg (see [[Blood gas tension]]).<ref name=\"Yacov2017\">  {{Cite book | authors= Yacov R, Derek K and Namasivayam A| title= Assisted Ventilation of the Neonate (sixth edition)| year=2017 | chapter=Chapter 10 \u2013 Blood gases: technical aspects and interpretation | publisher=Elsevier| isbn = 978-0-323-39006-4 }} </ref>\n\n\n==Oxygen exchange in the womb==\nDuring pregnancy, the mother\u2019s circulatory system delivers oxygen and nutrients to the fetus and carries away nutrient-depleted blood enriched with carbon dioxide. The maternal and fetal blood circulations are separate and the exchange of molecules occurs through the placenta, in a region called [[intervillous space]] which is located in between maternal and fetal blood vessels .<ref name=\"Wang Y & Zhao S\">   </ref>\n\nFocusing on oxygen exchange, there are 3 important aspects that allow it to pass from the maternal circulation into the fetal circulation. Firstly, the presence of hemoglobin F in the fetus allows a stronger binding to oxygen than maternal hemoglobin. Secondly, the mother\u2019s bloodstream is richer in oxygen that the fetus\u2019, so oxygen naturally flows towards the fetal circulation by diffusion.<ref name=\"Metcalfe1967\"> {{cite journal | authors=Metcalfe J, Bartels H and Moll W |title= Gas exchange in the pregnant uterus.  |journal= Physiological reviews |volume=47 |issue=4 |pages=782-838 |date=1967 |doi= 10.1152/physrev.1967.47.4.782 }} </ref> The final factor is related to the effects of pH on maternal and fetal hemoglobin. As the maternal blood acquires more carbon dioxide, it becomes more acidic and favours the release of oxygen by the maternal hemoglobin. At the same time, the decrease in carbon dioxide in fetal blood makes it more alkaline and favours the uptake of oxygen. This is called the Bohr effect or [[Haldane effect]], which also happens in the air exchange in the lungs.<ref name=\"Sarah2015\"> {{cite journal | authors=Griffiths S and Campbell J |title= Placental structure, function and drug transfer |journal= Continuing Education in Anaesthesia Critical Care & Pain |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=84-89 |date=2015 |doi= 10.1093/bjaceaccp/mku013}} </ref> All of these 3 factors are present simultaneously and cooperate to improve the fetus\u2019 access to oxygen.\n\n==Clinical significance==\n\n===Treatment of sickle-cell disease===\n[[Image:Sicklecells.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Increasing the body's production of fetal hemoglobin is used as a strategy to treat [[sickle-cell disease]].]]\n\n{{main article|Sickle-cell disease#Hydroxyurea}}\n\nWhen fetal hemoglobin production is switched off after birth, normal children begin producing adult hemoglobin (HbA). Children with [[sickle-cell disease]] instead begin producing a defective form of hemoglobin called [[hemoglobin S]] which aggregates together and forms filaments that cause [[red blood cell]]s to change their shape from round to [[sickle]]-shaped.<ref name=\u201dNIH_Sicklecelldisease\u201c> {{cite web |url= https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/sickle-cell-disease| title= Sickle cell disease| date= 2020-03-15|website= U.S. National Library of Medicine|publisher= NIH |access-date= 2020-03-15}} </ref>\n\nThese defective red blood cells have a greater tendency to form aggregates and block small [[blood vessel]]s, preventing blood supply ot tissues and organs. These invariably lead to so-called ''[[vaso-occlusive crisis]]'', which are a hallmark of the disease.<ref name=\" Deepa2013\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Manwani D and Frenette P|title= Vaso-occlusion in sickle cell disease: pathophysiology and novel targeted therapies|journal= Blood|volume= 122|pages= 3892-98|date= 2013|doi= 10.1182/blood-2013-05-498311}}</ref>\n\n\nIf fetal hemoglobin remains relatively high after birth, the number of painful episodes decreases in patients with sickle-cell disease and they have a better prognostic.<ref name=\" Idow2011\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Akinsheye I, Solovieff N Ngo D, Malek A, Sebastiani P, Steinberg M and Chui D|title= Fetal Hemoglobin in Sickle Cell Anemia: Molecular characterisation of the unusually high fetal hemoglobin phenotype in African Americans|journal= American Journal of Hematology|volume= 87|pages= 217-219|date= 2011|doi= 10.1002/ajh.22221}}</ref>\nFetal hemoglobin's role in reducing disease severity comes from its ability to disrupt the formation of hemoglobin S aggregates within red blood cells.<ref name=\"Ma2007\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Ma Q, Wyszynski D, Farrel J, Kutlar A, Farrer L, Baldwin C and Steinberg M|title= Fetal hemoglobin in sickle cell anaemia: genetic determinants of response of hydroxyurea|journal= The Pharmacogenomics Journal |volume= 7|pages= 386-394|date= 2007|doi= 10.1038/sj.tpj.6500433}}</ref> \n\n[[Hydroxyurea]] is a chemical that promotes the production of fetal hemoglobin and reduces the premature rupturing of red blood cells.<ref name=\"pmid18458272\"/><ref name=\"pmid7715639\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Charache S, Terrin ML, Moore RD, etal |title=Effect of hydroxyurea on the frequency of painful crises in sickle cell anemia. Investigators of the Multicenter Study of Hydroxyurea in Sickle Cell Anemia |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=332 |issue=20 |pages=1317\u201322 |date=May 1995 |pmid=7715639 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM199505183322001}}</ref> The fetal hemoglobin's reduction in the severity of the disease comes from its ability to inhibit the formation of hemoglobin aggregates within red blood cells which also contain hemoglobin S. Combination therapy with hydroxyurea and recombinant [[erythropoietin]]&mdash;rather than treatment with hydroxyurea alone&mdash;has been shown to further elevate hemoglobin F levels and to promote the development of HbF-containing F-cells.<ref name=\"pmid7677965\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Rodgers GP, Dover GJ, Uyesaka N, Noguchi CT, Schechter AN, Nienhuis AW |title=Augmentation by erythropoietin of the fetal-hemoglobin response to hydroxyurea in sickle cell disease |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=328 |issue=2 |pages=73\u201380 |date=January 1993 |pmid=7677965 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM199301143280201}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hemoglobinopathy.html Hemoglobinopathies]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040609153506/http://arbl.cvmbs.colostate.edu/hbooks/pathphys/reprod/placenta/transport.html Transport across the placenta]\n* [http://www.ascaa.org/ American Sickle Cell Anemia Association]\n* [http://www.sicklecelldisease.org SCDAA: Break The Sickle Cycle]\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hbsynthesis.html Hemoglobin synthesis]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020203114057/http://ntri.tamuk.edu/homepage-ntri/lectures/protein/hemoglobin/hempage.html Hemoglobin structure and function (archived February 3, 2002]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091029025455/http://fha.maryland.gov/genetics/hemo_f.cfm Hemoglobin F fact sheet (archived October 29, 2009)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20030330064928/http://www.isat.jmu.edu/users/klevicca/ISAT454/FetalHb.doc Fetal hemoglobin (doc file; archived March 30 2003)]\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hyguid.html Hydroxyurea in sickle-cell disease] (archived December 28, 2014 at [https://web.archive.org/web/20141228112837/http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hyguid.html])\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150329032048/http://scinfo.org/the-management-of-sickle-cell-disease-4th-ed/special-topics-chapter-26-fetal-hemoglobin-induction Chapter 26 Fetal Hemoglobin Induction; Management of Sickle-Cell Disease 4th Edition 2002 (NIH Publication No. 02-2117)]\n\n{{Globins}}\n\n[[Category:Hemoglobins]]\n[[Category:Infancy]]\n[[Category:Embryology of cardiovascular system]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox heteropolypeptide\n | heteropolymer = Fetal hemoglobin \n | polymer_type = 4 subunits, \u03b1<sub>2</sub>\u03b3<sub>2</sub>\n | protein_type = [[metalloprotein]], [[globulin]]\n | function = [[oxygen]]-transport\n | cofactors = [[heme]] (4)\n | image = Structure of Fetal Hemoglobin (HbF).png\n | image_source = Structure of Fetal Hemoglobin (HbF). The '''2\u03b1''' and '''2\u03b3''' subunits are in red and yellow, respectively, and the iron-containing [[heme]] groups in green. From {{PDB|4MQJ}}, by authors Soman, J. and Olson J.S.\n | SubunitCount = 4\n | subunit1 = Hb-\u03b11\n | gene1 = [[HBA1]]\n | locus1 = [[Chromosome 16|Chr. 16]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBA1#location?chromosome=16p13.3 p13.3]\n | subunit2 = Hb-\u03b12\n | gene2 = [[HBA2]]\n | locus2 = [[Chromosome 16|Chr. 16]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBA2#location?chromosome=16p13.3 p13.3]\n | subunit3 = Hb-\u03b31\n | gene3 = [[HBG1]]\n | locus3 = [[Chromosome 11|Chr. 11]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG1#location?chromosome=11p15.4 p15.4]\n | subunit4 = Hb-\u03b32\n | gene4 = [[HBG2]]\n | locus4 = [[Chromosome 11|Chr. 11]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG2#location?chromosome=11p15.4 p15.4]\n}}\n\n'''Fetal hemoglobin''', or '''foetal haemoglobin''' (also '''hemoglobin F''', '''HbF''', or '''\u03b1<sub>2</sub>\u03b3<sub>2</sub>''') is the main [[oxygen]] [[transport protein|carrier protein]] in the human [[fetus]]. Hemoglobin F is found in fetal red blood cells and it is involved in transporting oxygen from the mother's [[bloodstream]] to organs and tissues in the fetus. It is produced at around 6 weeks of pregnancy <ref name=\"David 1998\">{{cite book |last= Linch|first= David|date= 1998|title= Encyclopedia of Immunology (second edition)|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B0122267656001031 |publisher= Elsevier|isbn= 978-0-12-226765-9}}</ref> and the levels remain high after birth until the baby is roughly 2-4 months old.<ref name=\"Schechter2008\">{{Cite journal | author=Schechter A | title=Hemoglobin research and the origins of molecular medicine | journal=[[Blood]] | volume=112(10) | year=2008 | pages=3927\u20133938 | doi=10.1182/blood-2008-04-078188 }}</ref> Hemoglobin F has a different composition from the adult forms of [[hemoglobin]], which allows it to bind (or attach to) oxygen more strongly. This way, the developing fetus is able to retrieve oxygen from the mother's bloodstream, which occurs through the [[placenta]] found in the mother\u2019s [[uterus]].<ref name=\"Wang Y & Zhao S\">{{Cite book | authors= Wang Y, Zhao S| title= Vascular Biology of the Placenta| year=2010 | chapter=Chapter 2: Placental Blood Circulation | publisher=Morgan & Claypool Life Sciences }}</ref>\n\n\nIn the newborn, levels of hemoglobin F gradually decrease and reach adult levels (less than 1% of total hemoglobin) usually within 1 year of life, as adult forms of hemoglobin begin to be produced.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\">{{cite book |last= Wild|first= Barbara|date= 2017|title= Dacie and Lewis Practical Haematology (twelfth edition)|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B978070206696200014X |publisher= Elsevier|isbn= 978-0-7020-6696-2}}</ref> Diseases such as [[\u03b2-thalassemia]], which affect components of the adult hemoglobin, can delay this switch and cause hemoglobin F levels to be higher than normal in these patients.<ref name=\"Orapan2016\">{{Cite journal | author=Orapan S & Suthat F| title=Fetal hemoglobin regulation in \u03b2-thalassemia: heterogeneity, modifiers and therapeutic approaches | journal=[[Expert review of hematology]] | volume=9(12) |year=2016 | pages=1129\u20131137 | doi=10.1080/17474086.2016.1255142 }}</ref> In sickle cell anaemia, increasing the production of hemoglobin F has been used as a treatment, as it relieves some of the symptoms of the disease.<ref name=\"pmid18458272\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Lanzkron S, Strouse JJ, Wilson R, etal |title=Systematic review: Hydroxyurea for the treatment of adults with sickle cell disease |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |volume=148 |issue=12 |pages=939\u201355 |date=June 2008 |pmid=18458272 |doi= 10.7326/0003-4819-148-12-200806170-00221|url= |pmc=3256736}}</ref>\n\n\n==Structure and genetics==\nHemoglobin F, like hemoglobin forms found in adults ([[hemoglobin A]] and [[hemoglobin A2]]), have four [[protein subunit|subunits]] or chains. Each subunit contains a [[heme]] group with an iron element which is key in allowing the binding and unbinding of oxygen. As hemoglobin F has 4 heme groups, it can bind to up to four oxygen molecules.<ref name=brsphys>{{cite book |author=Costanzo, Linda S. |title=Physiology |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location=Hagerstwon, MD |year=2007 |isbn=978-0781773119 |url=https://archive.org/details/physiology00cost_0 }}</ref> It is composed of '''two \u03b1 (alpha)''' subunits and '''two \u03b3 (gamma)''' subunits, whereas hemoglobin A (97% of total hemoglobin in adults) is composed of two \u03b1 and two \u03b2 (beta) subunits.\n\nIn humans, the \u03b1 subunit is encoded on [[chromosome 16 (human)|chromosome 16]] and the \u03b3 subunit is encoded on [[chromosome 11 (human)|chromosome 11]]. There are 2 very similar [[gene]]s that code for the \u03b1 subunit, [[HBA1]] and [[HBA2]]. The protein that they produce is identical, but they differ in gene regulatory regions that determine when or how much of the protein is produced. This leads to HBA1 and HBA2 each contributing with 40% and 60%, respectively, of the total of \u03b1 subunits produced. As a consequence, mutations on the HBA2 gene are expected to have a stronger effect than mutations on the HBA1 gene.<ref name=\"Samaneh2018\">{{Cite journal | author=Samaneh F & Cornelis L| title=Molecular basis of \u03b1-thalassemia | journal=[[Blood cells, Molecules and Diseases]] | volume=70 |year=2018 | pages=43\u201353 | doi=10.1016/j.bcmd.2017.09.004 }}</ref> \nThere are also two similar copies of the gene coding for the \u03b3 subunit, HBG1 and HBG2, but the protein produced is slightly different, just in one [[amino acid|protein unit]]: HBG1 codes for the protein form with an [[alanine]] at position 136, whereas HBG2 codes for a [[glycine]] (see [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG1|NIH]).\n\n==When is hemoglobin F produced==\n[[File:Postnatal genetics en.svg|thumb|300px|[[Gene expression]] of hemoglobin before and after birth, also showing the cells types and organs where different subunits are being produced over time (data on ''Wood W.G.'', (1976). '''Br. Med. Bull. 32, 282.''') Figure last adapted by user Leonid 2.]]\n\nDuring the first 3 months of pregnancy, the main form of hemoglobin in the embryo/fetus is [[embryonic hemoglobin]], which has 3 variants depending on the types of subunits it contains. The production of hemoglobin F starts from week 6, but it's only from 3 months onwards that it becomes the main type found in fetal red blood cells.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\"/>\nThe switch to produce adult forms of hemoglobin (essentially Hemoglobin A) starts at around 40 weeks of gestation, which is close to the expected time of birth.<ref name=\"David 1998\"/> At birth, hemoglobin F accounts for 50-95% of the infant's hemoglobin and at around 6 months after birth, hemoglobin A becomes the predominant type. By the time the baby is one year old, the proportions of different types of hemoglobin are expected to approximate the adult levels, with hemoglobin F reduced to very low levels.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\" /> \n\nIn healthy adults, the composition of hemoglobin is hemoglobin A (~97%), hemoglobin A2 (2.2 - 3.5%) and hemoglobin F (<1%).<ref name=\"Caroline 2012\">{{Cite journal | author=Caroline T & Andrew L| title= Physiology of haemoglobin| journal=[[Continuing Education in Anaesthesia Critical Care & Pain]] | volume=12(5) |year=2012 | pages=251\u2013256 | doi=10.1093/bjaceaccp/mks025 }}</ref>\n\nCertain genetic abnormalities can cause the switch to adult hemoglobin synthesis to fail, resulting in a condition known as [[hereditary persistence of fetal hemoglobin]] (HPFH).\n\n==Binding to oxygen==\n===Why hemoglobin F has higher oxygen affinity===\nThe 4 hemes, which are the oxygen-binding parts of hemoglobin, are similar between hemoglobin F and other types of hemoglobin, including hemoglobin A. Thus, the key feature that allows hemoglobin F to bind more strongly to oxygen is by having \u03b3 subunits (instead of \u03b2, for example). In fact, some naturally existing molecules in our body can bind to hemoglobin and change its binding affinity for oxygen. One of the molecules is [[2,3-bisphosphoglycerate|2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG)]] and it enhances hemoglobin\u2019s ability to release oxygen.<ref name=\"Gerald 2018\">  {{Cite book | authors= Litwack G| title= Human Biochemistry | year=2018 | chapter=Chapter 8 \u2013 Glycolysis and Glocuneogenesis | publisher=Academic press| isbn = 978-0-12-383864-3}} </ref> 2,3-BPG interacts much more with hemoglobin A than hemoglobin F. This is because the adult \u03b2 subunit has more positive charges than the fetal \u03b3 subunit, which attract the negative charges from 2,3-BPG. Due to the preference of 2,3-BPG for hemoglobin A, hemoglobin F binds to oxygen with more affinity, in average.<ref name=\"Duane 2016\"> {{cite web |url=https://biosci.mcdb.ucsb.edu/biochemistry/tw-hbn/hbf/hbf-overview.htm\n|title= Comparing the molecular structure differences between HbF and HbA that affect BPG binding|last= Sears|first= Duane|date= 2016|website= https://biosci.mcdb.ucsb.edu/|publisher= Biosci Portal |access-date= 11 March 2020}} </ref>\n\n===Quantification of oxygen binding=== \nTo quantify how strongly a certain type of hemoglobin binds to oxygen (or its affinity for oxygen), a parameter called P50 is often used. In a given situation, P50 can be understood as the minimum concentration of oxygen needed for 50% of the hemoglobin molecules to bind to it.<ref name=\"Vibhu2006\">  {{Cite book | authors= Awasthi V, Goins E and Phillips W| title= Blood Substitutes| year=2006 | chapter=Chapter 43 \u2013 Liposome-encapsulated hemoglobin: history, preparation and evaluation | publisher=Academic press| isbn = 978-0-12-759760-7}} </ref> For example, Hemoglobin F has a lower P50 than hemoglobin A. This means that if we have the same amount of hemoglobin F and hemoglobin A in the blood and add oxygen to it, half of hemoglobin F will bind to oxygen before half of hemoglobin A manages to do so. Therefore, a lower P50 means stronger binding or higher affinity for oxygen. \n\nFor reference, the P50 of fetal hemoglobin is roughly 19 mmHg (a measure of pressure), whereas adult hemoglobin is approximately 26.8 mmHg (see [[Blood gas tension]]).<ref name=\"Yacov2017\">  {{Cite book | authors= Yacov R, Derek K and Namasivayam A| title= Assisted Ventilation of the Neonate (sixth edition)| year=2017 | chapter=Chapter 10 \u2013 Blood gases: technical aspects and interpretation | publisher=Elsevier| isbn = 978-0-323-39006-4 }} </ref>\n\n\n==Oxygen exchange in the womb==\nDuring pregnancy, the mother\u2019s circulatory system delivers oxygen and nutrients to the fetus and carries away nutrient-depleted blood enriched with carbon dioxide. The maternal and fetal blood circulations are separate and the exchange of molecules occurs through the placenta, in a region called [[intervillous space]] which is located in between maternal and fetal blood vessels .<ref name=\"Wang Y & Zhao S\">   </ref>\n\nFocusing on oxygen exchange, there are 3 important aspects that allow it to pass from the maternal circulation into the fetal circulation. Firstly, the presence of hemoglobin F in the fetus allows a stronger binding to oxygen than maternal hemoglobin. Secondly, the mother\u2019s bloodstream is richer in oxygen that the fetus\u2019, so oxygen naturally flows towards the fetal circulation by diffusion.<ref name=\"Metcalfe1967\"> {{cite journal | authors=Metcalfe J, Bartels H and Moll W |title= Gas exchange in the pregnant uterus.  |journal= Physiological reviews |volume=47 |issue=4 |pages=782-838 |date=1967 |doi= 10.1152/physrev.1967.47.4.782 }} </ref> The final factor is related to the effects of pH on maternal and fetal hemoglobin. As the maternal blood acquires more carbon dioxide, it becomes more acidic and favours the release of oxygen by the maternal hemoglobin. At the same time, the decrease in carbon dioxide in fetal blood makes it more alkaline and favours the uptake of oxygen. This is called the Bohr effect or [[Haldane effect]], which also happens in the air exchange in the lungs.<ref name=\"Sarah2015\"> {{cite journal | authors=Griffiths S and Campbell J |title= Placental structure, function and drug transfer |journal= Continuing Education in Anaesthesia Critical Care & Pain |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=84-89 |date=2015 |doi= 10.1093/bjaceaccp/mku013}} </ref> All of these 3 factors are present simultaneously and cooperate to improve the fetus\u2019 access to oxygen.\n\n==Clinical significance==\n\n===Treatment of sickle-cell disease===\n[[Image:Sicklecells.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Increasing the body's production of fetal hemoglobin is used as a strategy to treat [[sickle-cell disease]].]]\n\n{{main article|Sickle-cell disease#Hydroxyurea}}\n\nWhen fetal hemoglobin production is switched off after birth, normal children begin producing adult hemoglobin (HbA). Children with [[sickle-cell disease]] instead begin producing a defective form of hemoglobin called [[hemoglobin S]] which aggregates together and forms filaments that cause [[red blood cell]]s to change their shape from round to [[sickle]]-shaped.<ref name=\u201dNIH_Sicklecelldisease\u201c> {{cite web |url= https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/sickle-cell-disease| title= Sickle cell disease| date= 2020-03-15|website= U.S. National Library of Medicine|publisher= NIH |access-date= 2020-03-15}} </ref>\n\nThese defective red blood cells have a greater tendency to form aggregates and block small [[blood vessel]]s, preventing blood supply ot tissues and organs. These invariably lead to so-called ''[[vaso-occlusive crisis]]'', which are a hallmark of the disease.<ref name=\" Deepa2013\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Manwani D and Frenette P|title= Vaso-occlusion in sickle cell disease: pathophysiology and novel targeted therapies|journal= Blood|volume= 122|pages= 3892-98|date= 2013|doi= 10.1182/blood-2013-05-498311}}</ref>\n\n\nIf fetal hemoglobin remains relatively high after birth, the number of painful episodes decreases in patients with sickle-cell disease and they have a better prognostic.<ref name=\" Idow2011\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Akinsheye I, Solovieff N Ngo D, Malek A, Sebastiani P, Steinberg M and Chui D|title= Fetal Hemoglobin in Sickle Cell Anemia: Molecular characterisation of the unusually high fetal hemoglobin phenotype in African Americans|journal= American Journal of Hematology|volume= 87|pages= 217-219|date= 2011|doi= 10.1002/ajh.22221}}</ref>\nFetal hemoglobin's role in reducing disease severity comes from its ability to disrupt the formation of hemoglobin S aggregates within red blood cells.<ref name=\"Ma2007\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Ma Q, Wyszynski D, Farrel J, Kutlar A, Farrer L, Baldwin C and Steinberg M|title= Fetal hemoglobin in sickle cell anaemia: genetic determinants of response of hydroxyurea|journal= The Pharmacogenomics Journal |volume= 7|pages= 386-394|date= 2007|doi= 10.1038/sj.tpj.6500433}}</ref> \n\n[[Hydroxyurea]] is a chemical that promotes the production of fetal hemoglobin and reduces the premature rupturing of red blood cells.<ref name=\"pmid18458272\"/><ref name=\"pmid7715639\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Charache S, Terrin ML, Moore RD, etal |title=Effect of hydroxyurea on the frequency of painful crises in sickle cell anemia. Investigators of the Multicenter Study of Hydroxyurea in Sickle Cell Anemia |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=332 |issue=20 |pages=1317\u201322 |date=May 1995 |pmid=7715639 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM199505183322001}}</ref> The fetal hemoglobin's reduction in the severity of the disease comes from its ability to inhibit the formation of hemoglobin aggregates within red blood cells which also contain hemoglobin S. Combination therapy with hydroxyurea and recombinant [[erythropoietin]]&mdash;rather than treatment with hydroxyurea alone&mdash;has been shown to further elevate hemoglobin F levels and to promote the development of HbF-containing F-cells.<ref name=\"pmid7677965\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Rodgers GP, Dover GJ, Uyesaka N, Noguchi CT, Schechter AN, Nienhuis AW |title=Augmentation by erythropoietin of the fetal-hemoglobin response to hydroxyurea in sickle cell disease |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=328 |issue=2 |pages=73\u201380 |date=January 1993 |pmid=7677965 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM199301143280201}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hemoglobinopathy.html Hemoglobinopathies]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040609153506/http://arbl.cvmbs.colostate.edu/hbooks/pathphys/reprod/placenta/transport.html Transport across the placenta]\n* [http://www.ascaa.org/ American Sickle Cell Anemia Association]\n* [http://www.sicklecelldisease.org SCDAA: Break The Sickle Cycle]\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hbsynthesis.html Hemoglobin synthesis]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020203114057/http://ntri.tamuk.edu/homepage-ntri/lectures/protein/hemoglobin/hempage.html Hemoglobin structure and function (archived February 3, 2002]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091029025455/http://fha.maryland.gov/genetics/hemo_f.cfm Hemoglobin F fact sheet (archived October 29, 2009)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20030330064928/http://www.isat.jmu.edu/users/klevicca/ISAT454/FetalHb.doc Fetal hemoglobin (doc file; archived March 30 2003)]\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hyguid.html Hydroxyurea in sickle-cell disease] (archived December 28, 2014 at [https://web.archive.org/web/20141228112837/http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hyguid.html])\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150329032048/http://scinfo.org/the-management-of-sickle-cell-disease-4th-ed/special-topics-chapter-26-fetal-hemoglobin-induction Chapter 26 Fetal Hemoglobin Induction; Management of Sickle-Cell Disease 4th Edition 2002 (NIH Publication No. 02-2117)]\n\n{{Globins}}\n\n[[Category:Hemoglobins]]\n[[Category:Infancy]]\n[[Category:Embryology of cardiovascular system]]\n", "name_user": "Sciencingabout", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWhen is hemoglobin F produced:Added sentence about F-cells", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fetal_hemoglobin"}
{"title_page": "Brian Willoughby", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Brian Willoughby\n| image               = Brian Willoughby Milan.jpg\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1949|9|20|df=y}}\n| death_date                = \n| origin              = [[Glenarm]], [[County Antrim]], [[Northern Ireland]]\n| instrument          = [[acoustic guitar|Acoustic]] and [[electric guitar]]\n| genre               = [[rock music|Rock]], [[folk music|folk]]\n| occupation          = [[Musician]]\n| years_active        = 1960s\u2013present\n| label               = Cabritunes Records\n| associated_acts     = [[Cathryn Craig (folk singer)|Cathryn Craig]], [[Strawbs]], [[Mary Hopkin]], Dave Cousins, Nanci Griffith, [[Monty Python]], The Monks, Bridget St.John, High Society, New World, Jim Diamond, John Wright, Tom & Barbara Brown, Jack Hudson, Pete Ryder,  Bob E Baker, Reckless Johnny Wales, Michael Snow, Bill Lloyd,  Brian Connolly, Brian McDade, Mary Dawson, Bonnie Dobson, Maureen Kennedy-Martin, The Sharpees, Damian Wilson, Kenny Speirs.\n| website                 =\n| notable_instruments Acoustic & Electric Guitar, Ukulele, Mandolin. \n}}\n\n'''Brian Willoughby''' (born 20 September 1949) is a British guitarist. He has worked with many musicians, notably [[Dave Cousins]] and The  [[Strawbs]], [[Mary Hopkin]], as well as releasing solo work.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.strawbsweb.co.uk/hist/brian.asp |title = Brian Willoughby at Strawbsweb| accessdate = 26 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n(UK releases unless stated otherwise)\n\n===Albums===\n====Solo====\n*''Black and White'' (1998)\n*''Fingers Crossed'' (2004)\n\n====With other artists====\n*''Old School Songs \u2013 with Dave Cousins'' (1979)\n*''The Contractual Album \u2013 Monty Python'' (1980)\n*''Suspended Animation (The Monks)'' (UK band) (Gold Album in Canada 1981)\n*''Don't Say Goodbye  Strawbs'' (1987)\n*''Ringing Down the Years Strawbs'' (1991)\n*''The Bridge \u2013 with Dave Cousins'' (1994)\n*''Other Voices, Too (A Trip Back to Bountiful) \u2013 Nanci Griffith'' (1998)\n*''Baroque & Roll \u2013 Acoustic Strawbs'' (2001)\n*''Pigg River Symphony \u2013 Cathryn Craig'' (2001)\n*''I Will \u2013 with Cathryn Craig'' (2002)\n*''Blue Angel \u2013 Strawbs'' (2003)\n*''Full Bloom  \u2013 Acoustic Strawbs'' (2005) live at Natural Sound, Kitchener, Ontario, Canada (2004)\n*''Live at the Royal Festival Hall \u2013 Mary Hopkin'' (2005)\n*''Calling All Angels + Cathryn Craig'' (2009)\n*''Real World + Cathryn Craig'' (2013)\n*''Painting by Numbers + Mary Hopkin'' (2013)\n*''In America + Cathryn Craig''\n*''St.Pancras Old Church, London + Cathryn Craig''\nCountless other albums as session player \u2013 1969 \u2013 present.\n\n===Singles===\n*\"The King\" \u2013 Strawbs (1979)\n*\"That's When the Crying Starts\" \u2013 Strawbs (Canada 1987)\n*\"Let it Rain\" \u2013 Strawbs (Canada 1987)\n*\"Might as Well Be on Mars\" \u2013 Strawbs (Canada 1991)\n*\"Alice's Song\" \u2013 Acoustic Strawbs (2002)\n*\"Alice's Song\" \u2013 Craig & Willoughby (2009)\n*\"Calling All Angels\" \u2013 Craig & Willoughby (2009)\n*\"Rumours of Rain\" \u2013 Folk for Peace (2013)\n*\"Whole Wide World\" \u2013 Cathryn Craig & Brian Willoughby, featuring Righteous Brother Bill Medley\nCountless other singles as session player 1969 \u2013 present.\n\n===DVDs===\n* ''Complete Strawbs: The Chiswick House Concert'' (2002)\n* ''Acoustic Strawbs Live in Toronto'' (2004) filmed July 12, 2003 at Hugh's room\n* ''Rumours of Rain\"  + Folk for Peace (2013)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190412120610/http://www.highsocietyband.co.uk/ High Society website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100523002859/http://www.rumoursofrain.org/ Rumours of Rain website]\n*[http://www.strawbsweb.co.